<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, July 12, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
More Than 40 Die In Bombay Mudslide
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOMBAY, India (AP) -- At least 42 people died and 38 were injured when a
portion of a hill collapsed on unauthorized slums Thursday after more than 24
hours of heavy rain, city officials said. The tin and mud huts built into a
hillside that overlooks a road in eastern Bombay were smashed when the mud
loosened due to the heavy downpour since early Wednesday. Of 80 people taken to
hospital, 42 were declared dead due to injuries or suffocation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fiji Military: 4 Resorts Seized
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Two more tourists resorts were seized by protesters in
Fiji Thursday, bringing the number held to four, the military said. The U.S.
government urged all Americans to leave the country amid increasing unrest. The
seizures of the Buca Bay and Rukuruku resorts, which appeared peaceful, came
hours after the takeover of the upscale Laucala Island resort and a day after
the occupation of the Turtle Island Resort where ''The Blue Lagoon'' was filmed.
It was unclear if the takeovers were part of rebel leader George Speight's
efforts to pressure the Great Council of Chiefs, Fiji's traditional power, to
endorse his proposed Cabinet for an interim government.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House Rejects More Debt Relief
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ignoring a threatened veto, the House Wednesday rejected
most of the money President Clinton wanted for debt relief for poor nations. It
threw out an amendment to the foreign aid bill that would have added $390
million over the next two years for an international debt program, leaving the
figure at $69 million. ''I wish we had more but we don't have more,'' said
Republican Rep. Sonny Callahan of Alabama, arguing that under budget caps set
earlier this year the House is not permitted to increase proposed spending
unless an equivalent amount is cut from some other program.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Struggle for Progress at Camp David
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- President Clinton redoubled his efforts to push Israel
and the Palestinians toward a settlement of their half-century conflict at a
summit that was turning out to be difficult. Still, the White House said
Wednesday that there had been ''real engagement'' on substantive issues. Clinton
made plans to remain overnight after what he hoped would be a productive dinner
with Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton was wrestling with all the central issues.
Barak and Arafat met separately with Clinton at Camp David.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Episcopal Bishops Reject Same-Sex Rites
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Episcopal bishops voted against ceremonial rites for same-sex
unions Wednesday, a day after the provision was narrowly rejected by clergy and
lay delegates at the church's national convention. The votes don't mean the
debate is over, though. On Thursday, the bishops planned to discuss a proposal
calling for further study of the theological basis for consecrating same-sex
unions, with the findings to be presented at the next General Convention, in
2003.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N.H. House Impeaches Chief Justice
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- The state's chief justice was impeached by the
Legislature Wednesday in the first such action against a New Hampshire public
official since 1790. The 253-95 House vote sets the stage for a Senate trial
that could result in David Brock's removal for a host of alleged ethics
offenses, some of them more than a decade old. The vote came after seven hours
of debate.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Three found dead in N.Y. Building Collapse
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Three bodies were discovered Wednesday in the wreckage of a
pair of collapsed residential buildings. One of the buildings, a four-story
brownstone apartment building, collapsed Tuesday night on a quiet street in
Brooklyn, bringing down much of an adjacent three-story building. The roof of
the first building fell without breaking, making it more difficult for rescue
workers to look for survivors underneath.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell Thursday following a rally on Wall Street.
The dollar was higher against the yen. The Nikkei shed 232.69 points to
17,109.44 in early trading. In New York, the Nasdaq closed up 143.17 at
4,099.59. The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 56.57 at 10,783.76.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Messier Returning to the Rangers
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mark Messier, who captained the New York Rangers to the 1994
Stanley Cup, only to leave as a free agent three years later, will rejoin the
team for next season. The Rangers scheduled a news conference Thursday morning
to announce the deal that will reportedly pay the 39-year-old center between $10
million to $11 million for two years. In his third season in New York, Messier
led the Rangers to their first championship in 54 years. He also won five titles
with the Oilers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
