<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Military: 4 Resorts Seized  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL ALEXANDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Protesters in Fiji seized two more tourists
resorts Thursday, bringing the number held to four, the military
said. The U.S. government urged all Americans to leave the country
amid increasing unrest spawned by a two-month-old parliamentary
hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The seizures of the Buca Bay and Rukuruku resorts, which
appeared peaceful, came hours after the takeover of the upscale
Laucala Island resort and a day after the occupation of the Turtle
Island Resort where ''The Blue Lagoon'' was filmed.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear if the takeovers were part of rebel leader George
Speight's efforts to pressure the Great Council of Chiefs, Fiji's
traditional power, to endorse his proposed Cabinet for an interim
government or if his campaign was spiraling out of control.
</P>
<P>
   The chiefs began meeting Thursday morning to choose a new
president and vice president in line with an agreement signed
Sunday between Speight and the military leader who assumed power
after a May 19 coup. The deal is aimed at freeing the 18 remaining
hostages in Parliament. Nine were released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Laucala Island, formerly owned by late American media magnate
Malcolm Forbes, was sold last year by his estate. It has been
closed for several months, and no tourists were staying at the
pricey resort. Both Buca Bay and Rukuruku aim at the lower end of
the market. It was unclear how many tourists were at each one.
Forty tourists at Turtle Island Resort were released hours after
that takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Incidents of unrest have increased in recent days but most have
been peaceful, although five police officers were injured in a
police station takeover Wednesday at Labasa, which has turned into
a hotbed of Speight support.
</P>
<P>
   But there were growing concerns that the takeovers could spread,
possibly to Fiji's international airport near Nadi. The road from
Nadi to Suva has been blockaded, so disruption of the Nadi airport
also would essentially isolate the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The upgraded U.S. travel advisory urging Americans to leave the
country cited the ongoing unrest ''and the inability of local
authorities to respond to these problems.'' Last week, Washington
recalled the U.S. ambassador for consultations.
</P>
<P>
   Speight was meeting with the chiefs, the final hurdle in his aim
of overturning the Pacific country's elected government and
installing his own after already forcing a backdown by the military
regime.
</P>
<P>
   Speight's group appeared to be backing away from a promise to
release 18 remaining hostages -- including deposed Prime Minister
Mahendra Chaudhry -- on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Speight's spokesman Jo Nata said the military regime had not
finalized decrees enshrining the rebels' demands, including a broad
amnesty for political crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will torpedo the whole process,'' Nata warned on
Australian Broadcasting Corp. radio.
</P>
<P>
   But Politini said the amnesty is conditional on the release of
the hostages, not the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything that is happening in the country at the moment is
putting pressure on the chiefs,'' Nata said Wednesday. ''Suva is
almost under siege, the whole nation is in chaos. Isn't that what
you'd call holding a gun against the heads of the chiefs?''
</P>
<P>
   Speight has said the protesters are acting independently, but in
support of what he says is his cause -- indigenous Fijian rights.
But some of the disturbances clearly had little to do with
Speight's aims.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen guards were taken hostage on Tuesday by about 50
inmates in the maximum-security ward of Naboro prison, near the
capital, Suva. Police and soldiers deployed around the facility.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's agreement, the military agreed to scrap the
country's multiracial constitution, depose Chaudhry -- Fiji's first
prime minister of ethnic Indian descent -- and grant Speight and his
henchmen amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   The military seized control May 29 following violence and
looting in the wake of the Parliament raid.
</P>
<P>
   Speight's rebels are ethnic Fijians who say the Indian minority
has too much power.
</P>
<P>
   Indo-Fijians, whose ancestors were brought to the islands by
British colonialists over a century ago to work in the rich sugar
cane fields, make up 44 percent of Fiji's 812,000 people. Many
indigenous Fijians, who make up 51 percent of the population,
resent the Indo-Fijians' economic and political clout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
