<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Errol Flynn's Widow Remembers  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW J. ROSENBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ANTONIO, Jamaica (AP) -- As she sips rum and coke on a lazy
afternoon, the years melt away. In the soft Jamaican twilight you
can almost see the winsome young actress, fresh out of Kansas,
sailing the high seas and sharing an adventure with her roguish,
charming man.
</P>
<P>
   Four decades after the death of Errol Flynn, his memory and
legend are still strong in the Caribbean seaside town he adopted,
where his widow Patrice Wymore still lives, a respected town elder
and sometime cattle magnate.
</P>
<P>
   Married and widowed young, the sprightly 73-year-old retains a
youthful discomfort with the swashbuckling image Flynn cultivated --
and, according to tales still told with relish in these parts,
justly earned.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've stopped listening years ago,'' she says, dragging on a
cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   Sunglasses shielding her eyes, a wistful crack in her voice, she
describes their many forays to Jamaica as ''our retreat -- the place
to get away from the spotlights.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We were very busy doing nothing. We spent most days rafting,''
she says. ''That's not to say there wouldn't be a party on the drop
of hat.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn discovered Jamaica when his crippled schooner limped into
Kingston during a 1946 storm. He at first didn't know where he was,
but he grew to love the country, describing it as a paradise in his
autobiography ''My Wicked, Wicked Ways,'' published posthumously in
1976.
</P>
<P>
   ''Never had I seen a land so beautiful,'' he wrote. ''Everywhere
there is a blanket of green so thick that the earth never shows
through.''
</P>
<P>
   He found Port Antonio while motorcycling around the country.
Like other visitors over the years -- from J.P. Morgan and William
Randolph Hearst to Harrison Ford and Tom Cruise, whose 1988 movie
''Cocktail'' was filmed nearby -- he was struck by the wood houses
and stone mansions framed by tropical forest, seaside cliffs and
beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn began bringing Wymore here after they met in 1950 on the
set of ''Rocky Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I liked (Port Antonio's) simplicity,'' she says. ''It had that
kind of barefoot elegance, the people were kind and sweet. They
still are.''
</P>
<P>
   Fanciful -- if dubious -- accounts of Flynn's carousing are still
legend here.
</P>
<P>
   Vinroy Donaldson, 92, recalled seeing Flynn ''come into this
little rum shop where I was playing dominoes ... with three, four,
five women,'' and begin drinking the notoriously strong white rum
''straight down like a Jamaican!''
</P>
<P>
   An old taxi driver said he once saw Flynn drive a Cadillac into
a pool without ruining his cigar.
</P>
<P>
   ''I cut an imperial figure along the north shore of Jamaica,''
Flynn reported in his book, recalling various hijinks -- letting a
crocodile loose in Montego Bay -- and paying detailed homage to
''the beauty of the Jamaican females.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I presumed that she knew what my life was,'' he wrote of
Wymore. ''She knew the kind of man she was marrying ... a leopard
can't change his spots.'' Still, Wymore ''could cook Indian curry,
she could dance, she could sing, she was reserved, she had beauty,
dignity. ... If marriages are sensible, which I question -- I
thought I would give it a try.''
</P>
<P>
   Wymore confirms one popular story -- that Flynn won tiny nearby
Navy Island playing ''either poker or craps or dominoes.'' But the
deed was lost and the island is now a government resort.
</P>
<P>
   They also bought the once-glamorous Titchfield Hotel -- which
burned down in 1969 -- and dreamed of turning the area into a
tourist mecca. But financing and other problems intervened, and
Flynn died of a heart attack in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   One treasure remained -- the 2,000-acre ''Errol Flynn Estates''
cattle farm east of town, which Flynn bought in the 1950s and where
he once hosted British playwright Noel Coward.
</P>
<P>
   Wymore returned to the ranch permanently in 1967, after a
briefly revived career in which she appeared in a few movies,
including ''Ocean's Eleven'' with Frank Sinatra. She devoted
herself to the cows, including a herd of Jamaica Reds, and once
even won the Champion Farmer of Jamaica title.
</P>
<P>
   She was looking for a ''more enduringly satisfactory way of
life'' for her and Arnella, her daughter with Flynn who became a
model and died two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I always wanted to own a cattle farm when I was finished with
my career,'' Wymore says. ''I just had no idea it would be in
Jamaica.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Family's official site: http://www.inlikeflynn.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
