<HEADLINE> Whitman Won't Apologize for Photo  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- People who spend time on the streets here
say pat-downs by police are a way of life. Even a frisking by the
governor is not unimaginable, some say.
</P>
<P>
   But most are outraged by a 1996 photo that shows Gov. Christie
Whitman searching a black male in Camden. They are particularly
angered by the fact that Whitman appears to be smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's insulting. Her being the governor, coming into a city as
poor as Camden and doing this,'' said Ira Sapp, who showed the
picture to friends in a corner grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody felt the same way. It's not right. It's not fair,
and why is she smiling?'' he said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The photograph shows Whitman standing behind the man, who has
his arms spread and palms pressed up against a wall. The governor
is wearing jeans, a sweatshirt, a baseball cap and black gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Dupree said he is familiar with the man's position in the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yeah, I've been patted down by the cops. It's not a good
feeling and it's not something to laugh about,'' said Dupree, who
works in a barber shop.
</P>
<P>
   Ice vendor Ray English said he was disgusted by the governor's
actions.
</P>
<P>
   ''She thinks it's funny. This woman has no sense,'' English
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman has defended the search, and says two tours with the
State Police in 1996 helped push her to address Camden's dire
social ills. In the months before her visit, the state's poorest
city logged a record number of homicides.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said the crime rate has dropped dramatically, a new
county prosecutor is in place, federal authorities have targeted
municipal corruption and the state is attempting to take over city
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Since the picture became widely public, Whitman has repeatedly
rejected critics who say it is an example of racial profiling,
where minorities are targeted for searches by authorities. Troopers
offered her a suspect to search and she did, Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, whose protest over racial profiling shut
down the Atlantic City Expressway last year, said he will meet
Thursday with members of the Black Ministers Council of New Jersey
to plan demonstrations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
