<DOCNO> APW20000713.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Moves to Withhold Peru Aid  </HEADLINE>
By KEN GUGGENHEIM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The widely criticized re-election of Peruvian
President Alberto Fujimori could cost his country $10 million in
U.S. aid under a proposal receiving bipartisan support in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, sponsored by Sen. Paul Coverdell, R.-Ga., could
affect 10 percent of the $100 million Peru receives from the United
States and require the United States to oppose aid to Peru in most
votes of international financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell said the effort shows Congress plans to keep pressure
on Peru, ''that we don't just get bogged down, turn away and pay
little attention in our own hemisphere when we have instances that
really rattle the premise of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori was elected to a third term May 28 in an election in
which his only rival withdrew, alleging potential fraud and
unfairness in the electoral system. The Organization of American
States pulled out its election monitors after Peru refused to delay
the vote to ensure a fairer vote.
</P>
<P>
   After sending a high-level mission to Peru last month, the OAS
said Fujimori agreed to work with the organization and government
opponents to improve the judiciary, guarantee press freedoms and
fix flaws in the electoral system.
</P>
<P>
   However, political analysts and his opponents question
Fujimori's willingness to make reforms. Fujimori has ignored
international criticism in the past, including when he temporarily
closed the Congress and the Supreme Court in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's proposal would give President Clinton 90 days to
certify whether Peru has made significant progress toward restoring
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions would be applied if Peru hasn't made progress, though
most aid -- such as humanitarian and drug-fighting assistance --
would not be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell said the sanctions would be more than symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's put it this way: If I had 10 percent of your paycheck,
I'd have your attention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was an amendment to a foreign spending bill
approved by the Senate last month. The opposing ideologies of its
co-sponsors -- liberal Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., and conservative Jesse
Helms, R-N.C. -- reflect its bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Rep. Robert Menendez, D-N.J., will try to have the
language added to the House's foreign spending bill being
considered this week. Even if that fails, it could still be in the
final measure worked out by House-Senate conferees.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has not commented on the proposal. It has
generally followed the OAS' lead with Peru, though U.S. officials
have warned that Peru could face sanctions if it doesn't make
democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The Peruvian Embassy in Washington issued a statement
criticizing the proposal as contrary to an OAS assembly resolution
in Windsor, Ont., in June that didn't call for sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any unilateral action would not only be rash, but would also
oppose the spirit of the OAS assembly and could damage the effort
Peru is developing together with the hemispheric community to
fulfill the commitments made in Windsor,'' the embassy said.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time Congress has expressed displeasure
with Peru. In April, before the first round of the presidential
election, Congress approved a resolution warning Peru it could face
political and economic reprisals if there are problems in the
election process.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in approving a $1.3 billion package to help Colombia in
the drug fight, House and Senate conferees deleted language that
would have allocated up to $42 million for Peru in anti-drug aid.
Peru can still receive up to $40 million under general U.S.
anti-drug aid for countries in the Andes.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department background on Peru:
http://www.state.gov/www/background--notes/peru--0300--bgn.html
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell: http://coverdell.senate.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-13-00 0136 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000713.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Starr Aide Goes on Trial  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY MARGASAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Charles Bakaly III, the former independent
counsel spokesman, is going on trial on charges he misled a judge
about news leaks during the Monica Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson ordered the Justice
Department to prosecute the onetime aide to former Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr in a non-jury trial set to begin today.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend Bakaly misled Johnson, the chief judge of
federal district court in Washington, when he denied leaking
material in January 1999. They contend Bakaly later changed his
account to acknowledge he may have ''unwittingly'' confirmed
information for a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly is charged in the criminal contempt-of-court proceeding
with obstructing justice and making false statements to Johnson.
The Justice Department said that if Bakaly is convicted, it would
recommend a sentence of six months imprisonment or less.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times story at issue was written during impeachment
proceedings against the president, and said that Starr's office
concluded a sitting president could be criminally indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson on Wednesday turned down Bakaly's motion to dismiss the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The former spokesman argued that any false statements about his
conversations with a Times reporter were not material to the
central issue: whether the information in the story involved secret
grand jury matters.
</P>
<P>
   The former spokesman also contended that even if the information
did involve grand jury matters, it did not obstruct the
investigation of news leaks. Obstruction is a key element that
prosecutors would have to prove in order to convict Bakaly.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court eventually ruled that the Times article
did not reveal grand jury material, but Bakaly's original
statements denying any leaks came before that ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''Put simply, the materiality of a false declaration must be
measured at the point in time at which it was executed and filed
with the court,'' Johnson said, adding that Bakaly's argument
''strains logic past the breaking point.''
</P>
<P>
   She also ruled that Bakaly's alleged false statements about
leaks met the test for obstruction of justice because they caused
''added delay and expense'' to the independent counsel and FBI,
which investigated the leaked material. She said the statements
also resulted in more work for the court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
