<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Livingston County plans longest plastic span  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - Livingston County officials are laying
out plans to build the nation's longest plastic bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The plastic bridge will be more expensive to build than bridges
of steel and concrete, but the town of Avon's 40-foot plastic
project is likely to last decades longer.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not going to rot. It's not going to rust,'' said county
Highway Superintendent Don Higgins. ''Theoretically, there isn't
anything that can go wrong with it except actual impact - if
someone hits it.''
</P>
<P>
   In engineer lingo, the bridge will be of carbon fiber reinforced
polymers, or FRP. ''Basically, it's plastic,'' said Higgins.
</P>
<P>
   The FRP technology is relatively new in roads and bridgework,
according to the Cornell Local Roads Program.
</P>
<P>
   Construction on Avon's $515,000 bridge will start next spring,
with the federal government picking up $220,000.
</P>
<P>
   The federal cash comes largely because the size of this bridge
over the Conesus Lake Outlet will push the envelope of plastic
bridge design.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic bridges are rare in New York but one was successfully
built in Steuben County and another was built in Chemung County,
according to the state Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The current crumbling bridge was built in 1948 and has an 18-ton
weight limit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
