<P>
 Thursday, July 13, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fiji Leaders Release Hostages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Coup leaders on Thursday released the remaining 18
hostages in a two-month-old parliamentary hostage crisis, Fijian radio said. The
crisis has spawned increasing unrest in Fiji, including the seizure of at least
four tourist resorts, the military said. Coup leader George Speight and deposed
Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry hugged before Chaudry and other hostages were
loaded onto two trucks, the radio said. The trucks arrived to applause at the
Fiji Red Cross Society building, where the hostages were to undergo quick
medical checks. The release followed a deal Sunday, when the military agreed to
scrap the country's multiracial constitution, depose Chaudhry and grant Speight
and his henchmen amnesty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Steps Back From Peace Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- After two days of shuttling back and forth between the
Israelis and the Palestinians, President Clinton was stepping back from Mideast
summiteering Thursday, temporarily turning over the reins to Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright. As Clinton prepared to honor two previous commitments -- an
address to the NAACP in Baltimore and a medal ceremony in Washington -- the
White House adhered to its steadfast refusal to discuss the substance of the
talks. In addition to a series of informal encounters among members of the three
delegations, Wednesday's sessions included separate discussions by Clinton with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in the morning and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat in the late afternoon.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
More Than 40 Die In Bombay Mudslide
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOMBAY, India (AP) -- At least 42 people died and 38 were injured when part
of a hill loosened by monsoon rain collapsed on unauthorized slums, city
officials said Thursday. The tin and mud huts built into a hillside that
overlooks a road in eastern Bombay were smashed late Wednesday when the mud
loosened due to the heavy downpour since earlier in the previous 24 hours. Of 80
people taken to the hospital, 42 were declared dead due to injuries or
suffocation. City officials said those injured could not be given treatment
immediately because there were so few staff at the hospital closest to Balbati
Hillock.
</P>
