<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Than 40 Die In Bombay Mudslide  </HEADLINE>
By RAMOLA TALWAR BADAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOMBAY, India (AP) -- At least 42 people died and 38 were injured
when part of a hill loosened by monsoon rain collapsed on
unauthorized slums, city officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people live in tin and mud huts built into a Balbati
Hill, a hillside overlooking eastern Bombay, and workers said there
could be another 25 bodies buried under the debris that fell
Wednesday night. Scores of others were believed to have fled.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rescue work is still going on. The rain is making it very
difficult to move the debris,'' said P. Jadhav, a municipal
official.
</P>
<P>
   The annual monsoon rain has crippled transport services, with
clogged drains causing roads and railroad tracks to flood
throughout India's largest city. It took rescuers four hours to
reach the site because of the congestion and once they got there
small lanes jammed with huts leading up the hill slowed them
further.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said those injured could not be given treatment
immediately because there were so few staff at the hospital closest
to Balbati Hillock.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers helped municipal workers and civil defense staff, who
used bulldozers to move debris through the night. ''We are still
hopeful of finding survivors,'' said Sunil Chavan, a fire officer.
</P>
<P>
   Council member Pravin Chira said officials have warned of
landslide dangers. ''We told people to vacate the slums, but no one
listened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses and hospitals reported thin attendance since most
people headed back home rather than complete journeys of up to four
hours to reach their offices in downtown Bombay.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of newcomers to Bombay are being blamed for driving up
the city's population, pushing it from the world's fifth most
populated city today to likely the second by 2015. Bombay's
population of 15 million is expected to grow to more than 27
million in the next 15 years, placing it just behind Tokyo,
according to United Nations projections released last week.
</P>
<P>
   While municipal workers boast that 60 percent of Bombay's
residents are covered by family planning programs, they say the
rising population is the fault of the migrant slum population and
rural poor who flock to the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-13-00 0206 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000713.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solomon Islands Plans Defense Force  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONIARA, Solomon Islands -- The Solomon Islands plans to create
its first defense force as part of a plan to defuse almost two
years of deadly ethnic fighting in the Pacific island nation, the
new prime minister said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The force is part of the new government's ''Peace Plan 2000,''
said Prime Minister Manasseh Sogavare. That is his government's
first policy document aimed at ending an ethnic dispute over land
which has wracked the country.
</P>
<P>
   The defense force would oversee national security, do civil
works and assist in times of natural disaster. It wasn't
immediately clear when the force would be created.
</P>
<P>
   The peace plan includes setting a framework for peace talks
between two warring armed militias, amnesties for their members and
compensation payments to victims of the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Sogavare said he expected that militiamen from both sides would
join the new defense force, which would help rehabilitate the
fighters and ''bring these young people who are now used to holding
guns back to normal life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Solomon Islands is an archipelago nation of some 455,000
people spread over 10 large volcanic islands and four groups of
smaller ones 1,600 miles northeast of Sydney, Australia. It does
not have its own army, and the police force is the government's
armed domestic authority.
</P>
<P>
   The main island of Guadalcanal was the scene of a bloody and
drawn-out World War II battle, when U.S. Marines began their
island-hopping Pacific assault on Japanese forces after the attack
on Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic dispute escalated on June 5, when rebels from the
island of Malaita raided a police armory in the capital, Honiara,
seized the city and forced Prime Minister Bartholomew Ulufa'alu to
resign.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels were angry that over the past 19 months indigenous
people of Guadalcanal, known as Isatabus, have expelled 20,000
people who migrated there from nearby Malaita in recent decades to
find jobs and land. As many as 60 people have been killed in the
past few months.
</P>
<P>
   Since the June 5 uprising, a tense standoff has existed between
Malaitan and Isatabu factions.
</P>
<P>
   Sogavare -- elected by lawmakers after Ulufa'alu's ouster -- is
trying to bring the fighting groups together next week for formal
cease-fire talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-13-00 0207 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000713.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Leaders Release Hostages  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL ALEXANDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Coup leaders on Thursday released the
remaining 18 captives, ending a two-month-old parliamentary hostage
crisis that has spawned increasing unrest in Fiji.
</P>
<P>
   The hostage-takers held a traditional ceremony seeking
forgiveness, then rebel leader George Speight shook hands and
hugged deposed Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry before allowing
him, former Cabinet members and other hostages to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're all out,'' said military spokesman Maj. Howard
Politini.
</P>
<P>
   About 150 Speight supporters cheered as the hostages left. The
hostages also arrived to applause at the Fiji Red Cross Society
building, where they were to undergo quick medical checks.
</P>
<P>
   The release followed a deal Sunday, when the military agreed to
scrap the country's multiracial constitution, depose Chaudhry --
Fiji's first prime minister of ethnic Indian descent -- and grant
Speight and his henchmen amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   The military seized control May 29 following violence and
looting in the wake of the raid by Speight's gang 10 days earlier
on Parliament. Speight's rebels are ethnic Fijians who say the
Indian minority has too much power.
</P>
<P>
   The unrest has increased in recent days, possibly to take
advantage of the amnesty offer. Protesters seized two more tourists
resorts elsewhere Thursday, bringing the number held to four, the
military said.
</P>
<P>
   The seizures of the Buca Bay and Rukuruku resorts, which
appeared peaceful, came hours after the takeover of the upscale
Laucala Island resort and a day after the occupation of the Turtle
Island Resort where ''The Blue Lagoon'' was filmed.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear if the takeovers were part of Speight's efforts
to pressure the Great Council of Chiefs, Fiji's traditional power,
to endorse his proposed Cabinet for an interim government or if his
campaign was spiraling out of control.
</P>
<P>
   The chiefs began meeting Thursday morning to choose a new
president and vice president in line with the agreement signed
Sunday and aimed at freeing the 18 remaining hostages in
Parliament. Nine were released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Laucala Island, owned by late American media magnate Malcolm
Forbes, was put up for sale last year by his estate. It has been
closed for several months, and no tourists were staying at the
pricey resort. Both Buca Bay and Rukuruku aim at the lower end of
the market. It was unclear how many tourists were at each one.
Forty tourists at Turtle Island Resort were released hours after
that takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Incidents of unrest have increased in recent days but most have
been peaceful, although five police officers were injured in a
police station takeover Wednesday at Labasa, which has turned into
a hotbed of Speight support.
</P>
<P>
   But there were growing concerns that the takeovers could spread,
possibly to Fiji's international airport near Nadi. The road from
Nadi to Suva has been blockaded, so disruption of the Nadi airport
also would essentially isolate the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The United States upgraded a travel advisory Thursday urging
Americans to leave the country. It cited the ongoing unrest ''and
the inability of local authorities to respond to these problems.''
Last week, Washington recalled the U.S. ambassador for
consultations.
</P>
<P>
   Speight was meeting with the chiefs, the final hurdle in his aim
of overturning the Pacific country's elected government and
installing his own after already forcing a backdown by the military
regime.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything that is happening in the country at the moment is
putting pressure on the chiefs,'' rebel spokesman Jo Nata said
Wednesday. ''Suva is almost under siege, the whole nation is in
chaos. Isn't that what you'd call holding a gun against the heads
of the chiefs?''
</P>
<P>
   Speight has said the protesters are acting independently, but in
support of what he says is his cause -- indigenous Fijian rights.
But some of the disturbances clearly had little to do with
Speight's aims.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen guards were taken hostage on Tuesday by about 50
inmates in the maximum-security ward of Naboro prison, near the
capital, Suva. Police and soldiers deployed around the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Indo-Fijians, whose ancestors were brought to the islands by
British colonialists over a century ago to work in the rich sugar
cane fields, make up 44 percent of Fiji's 812,000 people. Many
indigenous Fijians, who make up 51 percent of the population,
resent the Indo-Fijians' economic and political clout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
