<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Welcomes Back Bill Bradley  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Papering over their acrimonious primary
battle, Vice President Al Gore welcomed fellow Democrat Bill
Bradley back to the presidential campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to have a great day together,'' he enthused to New
Jersey Democrats on the eve of his long-anticipated reunion
Thursday with Bradley at a midday campaign rally in Green Bay, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, in an interview with The Associated Press, Gore
emphasized that he agrees with Bradley on ''most of the issues''
and hopes to tap into his ''huge following around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I listened very carefully to his discussion of the issues in
our primary contest and, in many cases, I have tried to carry
forward the points of view he articulated very well'' on campaign
finance reform and child poverty, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   In Bradley's New Jersey home turf for a $750,000 pair of
Democratic National Committee fund-raisers Wednesday night, Gore
sounded intent on burying memories of the primary season. That
battle brought out the most aggressive campaigner in Gore, who
distorted his rival's agenda by alternately labeling Bradley a
reckless liberal and someone out to ''shred'' the government's
health-care safety net for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of Thursday's rally, the Republican National
Committee released a greatest-hits list of Bradley's primary-season
gripes about Gore, including: ''You are the elephant of negative
campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore was focused this week on projecting party unity -- at a
time when polls suggest he is having a harder time rallying
Democrats behind him than GOP presidential contender George W. Bush
is having with Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ''Throughout the primaries, even when they got pretty intense, I
maintained constantly and always that it was an honor to be in the
same race with Bill Bradley,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bradley has maintained a stubborn, almost
reclusive silence since he dropped out of the race March 9 and
tossed his support to Gore. Bradley's refusal -- then and since -- to
use the word ''endorse'' prompted taunts from Republicans and fed
speculation of lingering ill will for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Bradley partisans make clear he has not ruled out a
future presidential bid. To wit, he was in Chicago on Wednesday
night for a ''thank you'' party for supporters to ''keep his
network alive,'' one ally said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley spokesman Eric Hauser said the former senator from New
Jersey would finally use the ''E'' word on Thursday. ''This will be
an opportunity to formalize an endorsement and talk about why the
vice president is going to make a good president and is the right
choice,'' Hauser said.
</P>
<P>
   There are small hints that bruises remain.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign has not offered work to any of Bradley's top-
or mid-level former aides. And the wide net that Warren Christopher
has cast for counsel as he leads Gore's search for a running mate
has not included Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was Christopher's first meeting in 1992 when he helped
Bill Clinton identify a running mate, but Christopher has not
contacted Bradley at all this time around, Bradley allies said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gore campaign manager Donna Brazile, Bradley also
has yet to release the more than 300 delegates he accumulated
during the presidential primaries, none of which he won.
</P>
<P>
   Brazile called Bradley's hold on the delegates an untroubling
''procedural quirk.''
</P>
<P>
   As the incumbent essentially in control of the Democratic Party,
Gore and his operatives made sure from the start that Bradley's
delegates were denied 20-percent representation on any DNC
committee so they could not force any minority votes at the party
gathering next month in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-13-00 0231 </TRAILER>
