<HEADLINE> Heat Sabotages Border Crossings  </HEADLINE>
By RAUL LLAMAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NUEVO LAREDO, Mexico (AP) -- After walking for hours in the
sweltering desert heat, Margarita Alvarado had reached the edge of
the Rio Grande -- just yards from the U.S. border -- when she sat
down in the dirt and said she was going to die.
</P>
<P>
   Then she vomited, laid back in the dust, and she was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only thing I could do was go back and look for help, but
it was too late,'' said her brother-in-law, Juan Manuel Martinez,
19. The 32-year-old woman had reassured him just hours earlier that
she was fine.
</P>
<P>
   The tragic story Tuesday is recounted each year in the
blistering summer months, one of the most dangerous periods for
immigrants to be crossing the desert because temperatures regularly
rise above 100 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Sin Fronteras, a Mexican humanitarian organization that works
with migrants, told the government news agency Notimex this week
that 112 illegal immigrants -- mostly Mexicans -- died since October
trying to enter the United States. That's a jump of 40 percent from
last year, with the worst of the summer heat ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Border Patrol last week announced it is beefing up air
patrols to help find illegal immigrants in distress in Arizona's
deserts, the busiest illegal crossing point along the 2,000-mile
U.S.-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   The patrol has brought seven airplanes from other areas of the
country to Arizona to be used in sweeps along the border during the
next three months.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights activists say increased Border Patrol crackdowns in
California and Texas have driven immigrants to take more dangerous
routes through deserts and mountains to avoid being caught.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are seeing a steady increase that is alarming,'' Liliane
Loya, spokeswoman for Sin Fronteras, told Notimex. ''That tells us
that these are not simply accidental deaths -- that there exists a
clear relation: The deaths go up when control of the border areas
increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarado took the harrowing trip to be reunited with her husband
in Dallas, who had been working there as a cook for the past six
months. She was trying to cross into Texas when she died in the
northern state of Tamaulipas.
</P>
<P>
   She and her brother-in-law, who is from the northern Mexican
state of Durango, arrived in Nuevo Laredo on Tuesday morning in
search of a way to cross the border. They paid $40 to a migrant
smuggler who guided them on foot to a desolate region, away from
the cluster of border patrol agents on the other side of the border
in Laredo, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican soldiers they met on the way told them it was too
dangerous to continue in the intense heat. They ignored the
warnings.
</P>
<P>
   When Alvarado passed out, the smuggler and two other migrants
said they would get help once they crossed the border. Martinez
never heard from them again. He opted to abandon the crossing when
she died.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now the only thing left for me is to return,'' he said, ''to
bury the body of my sister-in-law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-13-00 0232 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000713.0028 </DOCNO>
