<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 02:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Dump Death Toll Rises  </HEADLINE>
By OLIVER TEVES
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Divina Alano wailed in grief
Wednesday as a mechanical hoe scooped up the body of her father
from a dark garbage-choked pool of water where their house once
stood.
</P>
<P>
   Her eyes were swollen from crying since Monday when a wall of
garbage, softened by heavy rains, crashed down on squatters'
shanties at Manila's largest garbage dump.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll climbed to 135 Thursday, and officials said
another 160 were still missing following the tragedy at the Payatas
dump that squatters called the Promised Land.
</P>
<P>
   At an open basketball court, Alano's mother, Gloria, made the
grim identification of her husband, Guillermo, whom she recognized
only by his short graying hair and pants. His face was disfigured.
</P>
<P>
   There was still no word about three missing family members.
</P>
<P>
   Dry-eyed, Rodito Camingawan waited at the basketball court for
volunteers to bring in the body of his wife; their son, 7; and
daughter, 6.
</P>
<P>
   The former cook said his family had been preparing to evacuate
early Monday because the water from a nearby creek was rising.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was looking for a neighbor to help us but when I returned
everything was gone, everything was covered,'' he said. ''I'll wait
until they stop digging, and if they stop before finding them,
there's nothing more I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Col. Jaime Canatoy, in charge of about 300 soldiers searching
for victims, said the military has been ordered to continue the
search until all have been found.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem is we do not know the exact figure of missing
people,'' Canatoy said.
</P>
<P>
   After digging for two days, rescuers largely gave up hope
Wednesday of finding more survivors. Canatoy said the methane gas
produced by the garbage would soon kill anyone buried under the
waste.
</P>
<P>
   The Alanos and Camingawans were among hundreds of squatter
families relocated about 10 years ago to part of the hilly Payatas
district of Quezon City in metropolitan Manila.
</P>
<P>
   ''We used to look downhill on the garbage dump, but it's grown
so much that now it towers above us,'' said Virgie Dimpal, a
neighborhood leader.
</P>
<P>
   The garbage mountain now stands about seven stories high and
occupies 74 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a man-made calamity. This is not a natural calamity,''
she said, blaming officials for letting the dump grow too high.
</P>
<P>
   Quezon City Mayor Ishmael Mathay said the city plans to move
about 300 families whose houses were destroyed to nearby Rizal
province.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado said all Payatas residents
should be relocated. ''We cannot allow people to live so
dangerously under the shadow of death in this dump site,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a smaller portion of the mountain of garbage
collapsed during heavy rains, but no one was injured or killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Payatas dump, along with a former dump in Manila's Tondo
slum district called Smokey Mountain, long has symbolized the
wrenching poverty in the Philippines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-13-00 0232 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000713.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
