<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fisherman Nets Catch of Alcohol  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway (AP) -- Fisherman Olaf Iversen thought he had made
the catch of the season when his nets began straining under a heavy
load while he was trawling for shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   It was a big catch, at least for the local customs office:
Iversen landed about 1,640 gallons of smuggled alcohol, making
national headlines Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had laid out the net, and was pulling it in when I saw that
there were a lot of oil barrels hanging on the net,'' Iversen was
quoted as telling Norway's largest newspaper, Verdens Gang.
</P>
<P>
   The 31 barrels were tied together underwater about 15 miles from
Stavern, a town in southern Norway. Iversen caught them Tuesday. He
summoned the coast guard when he realized what they contained.
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials said a ship may have dropped the contraband
and expected accomplices to collect it later. It was also possible
that smugglers lost the cargo or dumped it for other reasons,
police said. They said they had no suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Norway has some of the world's highest alcohol prices as a
result of high taxes meant to discourage drinking. The prices have
led to widespread smuggling.
</P>
</TEXT>
