<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alec Baldwin Stars in 'Nuremberg'  </HEADLINE>
By FRAZIER MOORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Get Alec Baldwin talking about his miniseries
''Nuremberg'' and he has plenty to say about Nazi atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   But however heartfelt his abhorrence of the Holocaust, Baldwin
wasn't drawn to ''Nuremberg'' by a desire to make a humanitarian
statement. Instead, he liked the dramatic conflict at the film's
core: two men in a duel of beliefs. (''Nuremberg'' airs Sunday and
Monday at 8 p.m. Eastern on TNT.)
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin plays Robert Jackson, an associate justice of the United
States Supreme Court who in 1945 was dispatched by President Truman
to the war-ravaged city of Nuremberg, Germany. There, Jackson would
be the lead prosecutor in a trial of 21 members of the Nazi high
command for war crimes committed by the Third Reich.
</P>
<P>
   Championing a civilized world, Jackson held all these men
accountable for the Nazis' ''mad and melancholy record'' against
the Jews. But the key defendant was Hermann Goering, notorious as
Hitler's second-in-command. As Jackson's bete noire, Goering was
charming, demonic and seemingly impenetrable.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a kind of tortoise-and-the-hare story,'' Baldwin says.
''Jackson arrives in Germany not quite certain what the
significance of the trial is. Then he goes into the courtroom
ill-prepared as a trial lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the same time, enter Goering, who has 1000 percent
mathematical certainty of who he is and why he's there and what he
wants to say on the stand. And the game is afoot.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to suggest that ''Nuremberg'' reduces the ensuing
courtroom combat to a two-man grudge match. For Jackson, who was
responsible for organizing the trial literally from the ground up
in the rubble of Nuremberg, the whole experience unfolds as one of
awful discovery -- as it does for anyone watching this powerful
film.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nuremberg'' has a splendid cast that, besides Baldwin,
includes Max von Sydow, Christopher Plummer, Brian Cox as Goering,
and, as Jackson's beloved assistant Elsie Douglas, former ''Law &AMP;
Order'' cast member Jill Hennessy.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Yves Simoneau from a script by David W. Rintels,
''Nuremberg'' is deliberative and unhurried, with a plush, mannerly
look that makes the wartime devastation seem all the more barbaric.
</P>
<P>
   This contrast is perhaps most pronounced in the scene when
just-acquired film of liberated Nazi death camps is entered into
evidence. Unreeling for four full minutes in the imposing, newly
reconstructed courtroom, this silent footage takes ghastly hold.
</P>
<P>
   As horrible as anything yet captured on film, the
black-and-white images sicken you today. But, chances are, you have
seen them before. Moreover, you view them from a half-century's
distance. For a 1940s courtroom audience, this unexpected footage
has shocking, graphic immediacy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Goering appears unmoved. ''Propaganda,'' he scoffs as
he is led from the courtroom back to his jail cell. ''Anyone can do
it. A little of this, a little of that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Elsie Douglas, clearly jolted, voices a more typical
response. ''How,'' she asks Jackson, ''could civilized human beings
do that to other civilized human beings?''
</P>
<P>
   He grimly replies, ''Maybe civilization is overrated.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the darker message of ''Nuremberg,'' which Baldwin is
discussing in a Manhattan hotel suite. Nattily dressed in a blue
suit befitting his film role, he munches gourmet M&AMP;Ms seized from
the mini-bar, explaining that he needs a sugar fix.
</P>
<P>
   Thus fortified, he describes the man he portrayed. ''Jackson was
a hero who left the comforts of postwar Washington and the Supreme
Court bench to go to war-torn Germany and explore the horrors of
the Nazi soul,'' Baldwin says admiringly. ''And with little
acclaim.''
</P>
<P>
   The yearlong hearing was conducted by an international military
tribunal of judges from the United States, Britain, France and the
Soviet Union. Nineteen defendants, including Goering, were found
guilty. Thirteen, Goering among them, were sentenced to death (but
Goering, ever defiant, committed suicide before his execution could
be carried out).
</P>
<P>
   For Jackson, who insisted that the defendants have a fair trial,
winning those verdicts with an airtight case was a rigorous
process.
</P>
<P>
   As Baldwin explains, ''Jackson's task during that year is to
answer the questions, 'Are the Nazis different from other enemies
in wartime? And if so, how?' In the beginning, he's not sure, and
he doesn't want to prosecute people simply for atrocities, because
any war is one big atrocity.''
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Jackson and his associates identified three
things that set the Nazis apart as uniquely evil.
</P>
<P>
   ''First was who the German people were in the civilized world,''
says Baldwin, listing his arguments in the present tense that his
character would have used. ''This is not some third-world country.
This is one of the preeminent civilizations in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ''Second, this is not a renegade operation. This is
state-sponsored genocide.
</P>
<P>
   ''And this is not an invading army that is dealing with their
vanquished captors. The Germans perpetrated this against their own
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no measure of justice or vigilance can finally
expunge this kind of evil from the human race. In the film, the
fresh-faced young American who guards Goering's cell grows in his
respect for the unrepentant Nazi. He promises to carry on the cause
after Goering is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ''That soldier is the spiritual grandfather of neo-Nazis in this
country today,'' Baldwin says. ''We wanted to make sure people
understood very clearly that the message did not only take root in
a German heart and mind and soul.
</P>
<P>
   ''It can take root in anyone, at any time,'' he says. As for
civilization? The jury is still out.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   For more information on ''Nuremberg'': http://tnt.turner.com
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Robert Jackson and the Nuremberg Trials:
http://www.britannica.com
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
