<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading Thursday, as
investors attempted to digest second-quarter earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 25.81 at 10,757.60.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mostly higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was up 0.10 at 1,493.02, and the Nasdaq composite
index was up 33.05 at 4,132.64.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors are acting cautiously in the wake of
Wednesday's rally, which many believe was a so-called technical
rally, or one in which stocks rise temporarily despite broader
trends that indicate stocks may be in a long-term slump.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's rally was spurred by better-than expected
second-quarter earnings report from Internet giant Yahoo!, which
served as a catalyst for a surge in technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The technology sector continued to advance Thursday, led by
Ariba, up 21.065 to 124.563 and Applied Micro Circuits, up 22.75 to
148.19.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues were about even with outnumbered decliners on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 136.94 million
shares, down from Wednesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 1.74 at 541.99.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.76 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 1.08 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.67 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
up 0.36 percent.
</P>
