<HEADLINE> Dow Slips 5 As Nasdaq Climbs 68  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading Thursday, as
investors attempted to digest second-quarter earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   In late morning on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average
was down 5.30 at 10,778.11.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 3.64 at 1,496.56, and the Nasdaq composite index was
up 68.61 at 4,168.20.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors moved cautiously in the wake of
Wednesday's rally, which many believe was a so-called technical
rally, or one in which stocks rise temporarily despite broader
trends that indicate stocks may be in a long-term slump.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Harrington, technical analyst with Wachovia Securities in
Charlotte, N.C., said investors have apparently taken temporary
comfort in the fact that energy prices appear to have stabilized
and the overall feeling that the Federal Reserve Board may be
fishished raising interest rates for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence of the cautious environmen, however, the Dow Jones
average was down slightly despite solid earnings reports from
General Electric and J.P. Morgan. General Electric was down $1 at
$52.50, while J.P. Morgan shares rose $2.69 to $125.25.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's rally was spurred by better-than expected
second-quarter earnings report from Internet giant Yahoo!, which
served as a catalyst for a surge in technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The technology sector continued to advance Thursday, led by
Ariba, up 20.375 to 123.875 and Applied Micro Circuits, up 24.312
to 149.75.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues were slightly ahead of decliners on the New
York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 325.59 million shares, up
from Wednesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 1.62 at 541.87.
</P>
<P>
