<HEADLINE> Bomb Explodes Near Bangkok Candidate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- A bomb exploded Thursday at a campaign
speech by the leading candidate in next week's election for the
Bangkok governorship, wounding eight people, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb went off about 20 feet from the stage where Samak
Sundaravej, 65, was addressing voters ahead of the July 23 vote.
Samak was not injured.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw an orange flash in front of me and I felt a shaking from
the explosion,'' Samak recounted in an interview with The Nation
television network. ''Someone yelled an electric generator had
exploded.
</P>
<P>
   ''People were running around and I could see some people were
injured and I wondered why there was no blackout. Then someone
shouted it was a bomb and they pulled me out of the area and I got
into a car.''
</P>
<P>
   The injured -- believed to be people listening to the speech or
passers-by -- were taken to two hospitals. Four were admitted
overnight and may require operations to remove shrapnel. The other
four were released after treatment, said Dr. Piya Totemchokechaikan
at Vejthani Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Samak, a longtime Bangkok lawmaker, said he had received a phone
call a few days ago from a man threatening to kill him but he had
not taken the threat seriously. Police were investigating.
</P>
<P>
   Samak leads in polls ahead of the election for governor.
Violence and intimidation are not rare in Thai elections, but this
campaign had not been marred before.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a very dirty thing to do. Whoever did it should be
ashamed,'' Samak said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
