<DOCNO> APW20000713.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Said Restricting Media  </HEADLINE>
By NICK WADHAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- A pattern of intimidation and pressure on the
Russian media casts doubt on President Vladimir Putin's stated
intention to protect press freedoms, an international delegation of
free press advocates said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The group, speaking after three days of talks with government
officials, journalists and publishers, said Putin has done little
to back up his remarks that a free press is crucial for a healthy
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Putin's stated goals are far from the reality in Russia
today,'' said a statement from the Russian Press Freedom Support
Group, made up of representatives from six international free press
groups. ''There is not a truly free and independent media in
Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent address, Putin stressed his commitment to protecting
media freedom. Media Minister Mikhail Lesin, recently named enemy
No. 1 by free press advocates for his belief that the government
must be able to protect itself against media slander, insisted
Wednesday that there was no media censorship in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Izvestia newspaper released Thursday
ahead of publication, Putin said he strongly supported free press,
but acknowledged that some outlets, hampered by high printing
costs, couldn't survive without working in someone else's
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the government wants (mass media) to be a really
independent, democratic instrument for the development of society,
it must give some preferences to that segment of the market,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Only when it is ''self-sufficient'' will the media ''reflect
real life, and not that which is wanted to be seen by people
ordering the information,'' Putin was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The international delegation said media intimidation took
several forms, citing the case of Radio Liberty journalist Andrei
Babitsky, who was detained by secret service agents in Chechnya in
January for not having proper accreditation, then disappeared for
weeks under mysterious circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   They also expressed concern about the criminal investigation
into media tycoon Vladimir Gusinsky, whose outlets have been
critical of the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Government prosecutors say they aren't trying to intimidate
Gusinsky. They said a raid by armed, masked tax police on his
Media-Most holding company was part of an inquiry into allegations
that he embezzled money during a privatization deal. Gusinsky was
later jailed for four days.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot excuse politically motivated prosecutions clearly
aimed at one of the free press, one of the very few independent
voices in Russia, and particularly the fashion in which it was
done,'' said James H. Ottaway Jr., chairman of the World Press
Freedom Committee and Senior Vice President of Dow Jones &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   In the Izvestia interview, Putin did not mention Gusinsky by
name, but said some businessmen ''are fighting more to save their
influence on the government than for the freedom of speech and
press.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Russian media are beholden to their owners' political
interests, and Gusinsky's NTV television openly backed President
Boris Yeltsin's re-election campaign in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Regional media, meanwhile, are often heavily controlled or
funded by local governments. Several Russian journalists have been
beaten or killed in recent years, in what human rights groups have
called attempts to stifle opposition voices.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation said it was particularly concerned about a
Russian media policy statement, submitted at a recent meeting of
European ministers, that called for preventing the ''use of
information with a view to undermining a state's political,
economic and social system.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the kind of language that we have not heard here in
Russia or abroad since the end of the Cold War, which we therefore
find extremely unsettling,'' said Ronald Koven, the European
representative of the World Press Freedom Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-13-00 1313 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000713.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes Marriage Tax Cut  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House has again passed Republican
legislation to cut taxes for millions of married couples, setting
up a showdown in the Senate and a late July, pre-GOP convention
confrontation with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans, meanwhile, reached agreement with Democrats
to remove parliamentary roadblocks and finish debate this week on a
House-passed bill to abolish estate taxes, another GOP priority
that Clinton has threatened to veto.
</P>
<P>
   In the first vote on that measure Thursday, senators rejected,
53-46, a Democratic amendment that would sharply increase the
amount of an estate exempt from taxes -- it is now $675,000 per
individual, more for small businesses and family farms -- but would
stop short of complete abolition.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats planned to offer other amendments that would divert
some of the money in the GOP bill to such things as a college
tuition tax credit and a Medicare prescription drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're saying there are other priorities,'' said Sen. Byron
Dorgan, D-N.D.
</P>
<P>
   The 269-159 vote by which the House passed the 10-year, $182
billion ''marriage penalty'' tax cut Wednesday was a virtual mirror
image of a February vote on the same bill. The move was necessary
because Senate Democrats filibustered the first bill, forcing GOP
leaders to pass it again under budget rules that limit debate and
amendments.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did it once, but it was held up in the Senate,'' said House
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. ''It's something we've promised the
American people, and we'll get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill is aimed at the estimated 25 million two-income married
couples who pay higher income taxes than they would if single, but
it also gives a tax cut to virtually all married people who file
joint tax returns. It would gradually expand the bottom 15 percent
income tax bracket so that by 2007 it is double the bracket for two
single people and would boost the standard deduction to twice that
of singles in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also would raise the income cap to allow more
lower-income couples to claim the earned income tax credit and
would ensure that couples who claim certain personal credits, such
as the $500 per-child credit, do not run afoul of the complex
alternative minimum tax.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate intends to take up its 10-year, $248 billion version
of the bill later this week. A House-Senate conference committee
would be named to work out differences, which mainly center on how
the next-highest 28 percent tax bracket is treated.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are rushing to get the bill to Clinton before the
start of the Republican National Convention on July 31, calculating
that a veto gives them a popular issue to exploit. If the president
were to sign the measure, the GOP could use that to fight Vice
President Al Gore's claim that Republicans are running a
''do-nothing'' Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats charged that the measure was nothing but ''a political
statement,'' in the words of Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y. They tried
to force Republicans to attach a government-run Medicare
prescription drug benefit that Clinton has made a condition of
signing the tax cut into law. But that effort was rejected by a
230-197 vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there's a nexus between marriage penalty and
prescription drugs,'' Hastert said. ''They're at risk of being
do-nothing Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Before taking up the marriage tax cut, the Senate intends to
begin serious debate on the 10-year, $104 billion Republican bill
that would gradually scrap federal estate taxes by 2010. Passage
could come as early as Thursday evening, or possibly Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats plan to offer a series of amendments, including a
Medicare prescription drug benefit, along with an estate tax
alternative that increases exemptions for family farms and small
businesses that suffer most from the tax. Clinton has endorsed the
Democratic approach, saying complete repeal is unnecessary and
would mainly help the wealthiest people in America.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's staggering to see what the Republicans will do in the
name of tax reduction, benefiting the very, very wealthiest in this
country,'' said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   The marriage penalty bill is H.R. 4810.
</P>
<P>
   The estate tax bill is H.R. 8.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Congress: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
