<HEADLINE> German Teens Sentenced for Arson  </HEADLINE>
By JOCHEN WIESIGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   GERA, Germany (AP) -- Two teen-agers who threw Molotov cocktails
at a synagogue in eastern Germany on Hitler's birthday were
convicted Thursday and sentenced to prison, a verdict meant to show
that Germany takes combating far-right violence seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Andreas John, 18, drew a three-year term and Carsten Haag, 17,
received two years and three months for an attack that provoked
outrage across Germany.
</P>
<P>
   They had confessed to throwing beer bottles filled with oil at
the building in Erfurt, capital of Thuringia state, on the night of
April 20, saying they wanted to show ''Nazism is still alive.'' At
the start of the trial on Tuesday, both had expressed regret and
told the court they were no longer neo-Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Their lawyers had sought lenient sentences, citing the change of
views. Federal prosecutors had asked for 3&AMP;frac12; years.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum possible sentence under juvenile law in Germany is
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   A third defendant, David Koehler, 18, who was charged with being
an accessory to the crime, was given probation. He had admitted
driving the other two to Erfurt, but said he was unaware of what
they were planning to do.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was little damage because the Molotov cocktails
failed to ignite, the attack prompted a nationwide outcry against
neo-Nazi violence and expressions of solidarity with Germany's
small Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   ''What are Jews to think after all their painful experiences
when 17- and 18-year-olds try to set a synagogue on fire in today's
Germany?'' said presiding judge Erich Rachor, adding that one of
the defendants had displayed ''unbearable hate toward Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict sent a signal that neo-Nazi ideas ''have no place in
our society and must be fought with full force,'' said Joerg van
Essen, a lawmaker for the opposition Free Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors had taken over the Erfurt case as part of a
drive begun this year to send a signal of deterrence through swift
convictions and sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   But even a leader of Germany's ruling coalition insisted the
government must do more to combat racism and anti-Semitism among
young Germans. Attacks -- from vandalism at Jewish graves to
beatings of foreigners by neo-Nazi skinheads -- are a near daily
occurrence in Germany, home to 2 million Turks and about 5 million
other foreign nationals.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's Cabinet agreed Wednesday to get
government ministries working on how best to combat extremism, a
sign of concern especially about former communist East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In some eastern towns, young neo-Nazis hold sway over
schoolyards and streets to such a degree that foreigners or German
youths who don't share their views risk a beating or simply avoid
those parts of town.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Greens party, Schroeder's junior coalition
partner, said she wants the federal government to pump money into
anti-extremist education in schools and counseling for neo-Nazi
victims.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are noticing that these extreme-right views turn up at the
kitchen table and are supported by the families,'' Greens
chairwoman Renate Kuenast said on German radio. ''That makes it
even more important for political leaders to intervene.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
