<HEADLINE> 'Tabletop' Play Proves Fascinating  </HEADLINE>
by 
V0814-----
r e *1404AP-Theater-Tableto     07-13 0335
*1404 AP-Theater-Tabletop,0335   
'Tabletop' Play Proves Fascinating   
An AP Entertainment Review
By MARY CAMPBELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- ''Tabletop,'' a play about making TV
commercials, sounds dim and proves fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Ackerman, who wrote it, directs plays in Chicago and has for
several years been property master for commercials, films and
''Saturday Night Live.'' His expertise, director Connie Grappo's
skill and some on-target acting performances make the play fairly
jump from the stage at the off-Broadway Working Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tabletop'' opened Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The two key performances are perfectly realized. Stand-up
comedian Rob Bartlett, host of radio and TV's ''Imus in the
Morning'' plays Marcus, who specializes in making TV commercials
shot on tabletops. He is a tyrant who believes in fear and tension
and mercilessly berates his crew. There's nothing funny about
Marcus. The only reason his crew doesn't hate him is that they
recognize and respect his love for commercials and his driving need
to make them.
</P>
<P>
   Opposite Bartlett is Jeremy Webb in a perfectly nuanced
performance as Ron, a kind of office boy who sprays the fruit
before TV shots.
</P>
<P>
   Ron is an idealist who thinks commercials are a boon to mankind
and should be made artistically. He's also an innovator who knows
how to make a liquid look thicker, or wire a bunch of grapes
upright so the wiring doesn't show.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Nolen, like Webb is a veteran of regional theater, plays
Jeffrey, the props man. Bossy, sharp-tongued Andrea is played by
Elizabeth Hanley Rice, who has acted on- and off-Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Egos flare, ambitions bloom and wilt. Cameraman Oscar (Harvey
Blanks) dreams of opening a hardware store in New Jersey. Dave the
lighting man (Dave Koenig) is a homosexual struggling to stay in
the closet. Their lives, intersecting with the TV commercial -- that
most ephemeral and ridiculed of modern phenomena -- make engrossing
drama.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
