<HEADLINE> Chechen Leader Ready To Talk Peace  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAIRTUP, Russia (AP) -- Chechnya's self-declared separatist
president said he was prepared to negotiate a peace with Moscow,
but that rebels in his homeland would fight on indefinitely if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are trying to convince Russia that it is useless,'' to
continue the war, Aslan Maskhadov said in an interview with the
Azerbaijani News Service filmed at an undisclosed location in the
southern mountains of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview released Thursday, Maskhadov looked relaxed and
smiled on several occasions. He sat before a carpet hung on a wall
and sipped tea.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov, who has been in hiding for months, derided Russian
attempts to form a pro-Moscow administration in Chechnya as clumsy
and doomed, and called for peace talks under the auspices of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am ready to sit down at the negotiating table,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov has offered talks before, but Russia has rejected
negotiations with the rebels, offering only the possibility of
amnesty in exchange for the guerrillas' surrender. Meanwhile,
ambushes, mines and sniper attacks have taken a steady toll on
Russian forces despite their formal control of most of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov, who led separatist forces during their victorious
1994-96 war with Moscow, said new recruits were boosting rebel
ranks and that most Chechens despised Russian rule and would not
abide by the puppet government.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin, meanwhile, said in an
interview published in Izvestia newspaper that ''patience'' will be
necessary in resolving the Chechen conflict, and that military
might alone won't bring peace to the region.
</P>
<P>
   ''Large-scale social rehabilitation (and) effective political
processes'' will also be required, he said, apparently referring to
work with the pro-Moscow administration.
</P>
<P>
   That administration convinced a 200-strong rebel band commanded
by warlord Turpal-ali Atgeriyev to lay down arms and surrender in
exchange for amnesty, Deputy Chief of the General Staff Col. Gen.
Valery Manilov said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Manilov said that ''the situation is under control, and no one
will allow the rebels to impose their terms on us,'' the Interfax
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Yet fighting continued.
</P>
<P>
   Two Russian police officers were wounded Wednesday when they
were fired on while patrolling a stretch of railroad track across
the Argun River near Grozny, military officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Two large mines were destroyed near the town of Kurchaloi, one
200 yards from a Russian checkpoint and another along a roadside
near the town, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said Thursday they had arrested a Chinese
citizen who had been training to become a terrorist in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Security Service said they detained Kurban Abdulaik,
a member of the Muslim Uighur ethnic group of western China, near
Chechnya and have extradited him to China, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, Manilov said Moscow will stop announcing
casualty totals in the 11-month war. The military will release only
weekly totals of wounded and dead, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''About these tragic numbers ... my heart can't bear presenting
the total,'' he explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
