<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton OKs Colombia, Kosovo Aid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton signed an $11.2 billion
measure Thursday that includes a tenfold increase in money for
Colombia's war against drugs and funds for U.S. peacekeeping forces
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Colombia is a strong ally and the oldest democracy
in Latin America. ''Today it is under attack -- from civil conflict
and drug trafficking that fuels violence, undercuts honest
enterprise and undermines public confidence in democracy,'' the
president said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure provides $1.3 billion to help equip and train
Colombian forces battling cocaine and heroin producers controlling
southern sections of the country. As the bill moved through
Congress, some lawmakers warned of being dragged into a
Vietnam-type of unwinnable war.
</P>
<P>
   ''As Colombians fight to build their democracy and block the
illegal drug trade, they are fighting for all of us,'' Clinton said
in a signing statement. ''If they are willing to take up the fight,
we should be willing to take on some of the cost.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert said the drug package was ''a
shared accomplishment between the Republican House and the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   The $11.2 billion bill was twice the amount that Clinton
requested four months ago. Lawmakers more than doubled Clinton's
defense request to $6.4 billion and also included hundreds of
millions for election-year, home-state projects ranging from New
York City's proposed Second Avenue subway to the crabbing industry
in Alaska, Washington state and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   The package contained $2 billion for U.S. peacekeeping troops in
Kosovo; $661 million to help New Mexico recover from blazes that
charred Los Alamos and other communities; and $350 million for
fighting other wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Kosovo money, Clinton said, ''NATO forces won
the war in 78 days; it will take longer to secure a stable peace. I
applaud Congress for sending a message that we will stand by our
troops until the job is done.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also $360 million to help North Carolina and other
states hit by last September's Hurricane Floyd and farm problems,
and $600 million to help low-income families pay their utility
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also managed to find $45 million to buy a Gulfstream
executive jet for the Coast Guard's commandant; $8.4 million to
help the White House reconstruct the lost e-mails that
congressional investigators are hunting; and $17.5 million to fix
some of the Capitol's numerous fire hazards.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also had $7 million to help Hawaiian fishing boats
avoid snagging sea turtles; $112 million to reimburse California,
Arizona, New Mexico and Texas for costs of dealing with illegal
immigrants and smuggling; and $2 million to help refurbish the rail
link between Danbury and Norwalk, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the legislation ''is disappointing for what it
leaves out.'' He complained that it lacks money for debt relief for
the world's poorest countries and ''offers inadequate funding'' for
Mozambique and other southern African nations devastated by
flooding. Furthermore, he said that it ''undercuts U.S. interests''
by omitting money for U.N. peacekeeping operations in Southeast
Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
