<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lou Gehrig's disease sufferer jumps off parking garage  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - A man killed himself Thursday by
jumping off a casino parking garage, the third such suicide in as
many months.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Pidgeon, 51, of Blackwood, who suffered from Lou Gehrig's
disease, plunged 120 feet from the roof of the Caesars Atlantic
City Hotel Casino garage about 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   He died at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Gloucester Township had been searching for Pidgeon
since Monday, when family members reported him missing, according
to Deputy Chief Michael Senatore of the Gloucester Township Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   He suffered from Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis, an incurable,
fatal nerve disorder that robs its victims of even basic movements
like swallowing.
</P>
<P>
   The disease is named after New York Yankees great Lou Gehrig,
who died of it in 1941. It wasn't clear how long ago Pidgeon was
diagnosed with the disease or how far it had progressed. Typically,
victims live between two and five years after being diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   He was still able to walk, talk and drive a car, according to
Senatore. His adult son, who reported him missing, said he was
worried because Pidgeon would become disoriented and could suffer
seizures if he didn't have his medication, according to Senatore.
</P>
<P>
   Pidgeon had recently lost his job, but Senatore didn't know what
it had been or where.
</P>
<P>
   No suicide note was left at the scene, according to Sgt. Michael
Tullio, a spokesman for the Atlantic City Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Victims of ALS sometimes look to suicide after being diagnosed
because they fear the paralysis that awaits them, according to Mary
Lyons, vice president of The ALS Association, of Calabasas Hills,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Youk, 53, of Waterford, Mich., whose assisted 1998
suicide at the hands of Dr. Jack Kevorkian was televised on ''60
Minutes,'' suffered from the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although patients want to know about their options, it's not
common that they go ahead and make that choice. The majority of
people are dying a quiet and peaceful death,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tullio, a police spokesman, said police were trying to find out
where Pidgeon was between Monday and Thursday. He appealed for
anyone with information to contact Atlantic City police.
</P>
<P>
   ''God, isn't it awful?'' said Diana Whiteman, a bartender at
DeFeo's Lounge, which is located down the block from the Missouri
Avenue sidewalk where Pidgeon landed. ''People were staying in here
this morning because they didn't want to go out and have to see the
body.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the third casino parking garage suicide this year.
</P>
<P>
   On April 4, a dealer at the Sands Hotel Casino jumped to his
death from the Trump Plaza parking garage. On May 26, a former
employee of Trump Marina leaped from the garage there.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, three people died in casino jumps. One jumped from
the Resorts Atlantic City, one from the Caesars garage and one from
a Trump Plaza tower.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   ALS Association: http://www.alsa.org
</P>
<P>
   American Association of Suicidology: http://www.suicidology.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-13-00 1644 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000713.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal Reserve May Buy Less  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve, which is having to adjust
its portfolio management because of shrinking debt issues, may buy
$30 billion less of Treasury securities over the next two years, a
Treasury official indicated Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''While many things may change over the next 24 months, based on
the Federal Reserve's current holdings and Treasury's current
auction sizes, the new procedure could lead to net redemptions
approaching $30 billion in coupon securities,'' Gary Gensler,
Treasury's under secretary for domestic finance, said in a speech
to the Bond Market Association in New York.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Fed may be forced to go the secondary market to
replace the securities it can't buy directly from Treasury, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Gensler also said that Treasury, against the backdrop of budget
surpluses and efforts to reduce debt, is continuing to consider
eliminating the one-year Treasury bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a limited number of statutory provisions that
reference the one-year bill for the purpose of setting interest
rates,'' he said. ''We are pleased with the progress to date of our
discussions with Congress to designate appropriate alternative
reference rates for student loans rates and other statutorily set
rates that currently reference the one-year bill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-13-00 1649 </TRAILER>
