<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000713.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Sprawl will eventually overwhelm watershed, hurt Bay  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER THORNE
<TEXT>
<P>
   A leading Chesapeake Bay watchdog group released a report
Thursday that warns of suburban sprawl so great it will envelop
3,500 square miles of open land in the bay's watershed over the
next quarter century.
</P>
<P>
   The new highways, parking lots and traffic congestion will add
to the pollution and runoff that harms the delicate health of the
bay, warned the Chesapeake Bay Foundation report, titled ''Land and
the Chesapeake.''
</P>
<P>
   A statistical snapshot of current land use patterns in the six
states that make up the Chesapeake Bay's watershed - Maryland,
Virginia, Pennsylvania, and parts of Delaware, New York and New
Jersey - the report predicts that newly minted agreements to
control sprawl and development may not go far enough to protect the
estuary.
</P>
<P>
   ''The future of the bay is at risk,'' said Lee Epstein, land use
manager for the Annapolis, Md.-based foundation. ''All the progress
we've made and continue to make will be for nothing if we end up
developing 3,500 square miles over the next 15 or 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The report comes two weeks after an agreement was forged between
several of the Chesapeake Bay states to reduce sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   Governors of the states pledged to reduce by 30 percent the rate
of urban sprawl in the bay region by 2012. They also resolved to
permanently protect 1.6 million acres around the bay and restore
25,000 acres of wetlands by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   The accord was signed by Maryland Gov. Parris Glendening; Gov.
Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania; Gov. Jim Gilmore of Virginia; and Mayor
Anthony Williams of Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The report comes just days after Glendening was made chairman of
the National Governors' Association with a promise to advocate for
controlled growth.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast of dwindling land serves as a warning, Epstein
said, that if the agreement and other measures don't curb sprawl,
drastic results will follow.
</P>
<P>
   The report predicts the population living in the six-state bay
watershed will grow from 15.5 million to more than 18 million by
2020. It also found demand for new homes will develop 90,000 acres
of meadows, forest and farmland every year to build suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Building new homes, Epstein said, should not necessarily mean
bulldozing forests and paving new roads for suburbs. New buildings
can go up in existing towns and cities, ''filling in'' empty
pockets or poorly planned areas, without paving over more
watershed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But developers are only meeting demand, said Larry Schaffert,
president of the Maryland State Builders Association. He is also
owner of Schaffert Construction Inc., in Myersville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe in comprehensive, planned growth, but it may come
down to what people want and what they can afford,'' Schaffert
said. ''People are moving to the suburbs because that's where they
want to live.''
</P>
<P>
   The goals of the Chesapeake Bay Foundation are already in place
in Maryland as a key element of Glendening's ''Smart Growth''
initiative, said Michelle Byrnie, a spokeswoman for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here in Maryland, we are taking a very aggressive approach to
preserving open space and farm land, and directing growth to where
it makes sense,'' Byrnie said. ''And we are seeing the results.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, during the five years Glendening has been in
office, Maryland has permanently preserved 187,000 acres of land.
And in the last two years, the state has preserved more land than
was developed, Byrnie said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-13-00 1651 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000713.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that were moving substantially or trading
heavily Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE
Capital One Financial Corp., rose $1.813 to $51.313
</P>
<P>
   Capital One Financial, a credit-card issuer, reported
second-quarter earnings of 54 cents a share, up from 41 cents a
year earlier. The company cited an increase in the number of charge
accounts for the rise in profits.
</P>
<P>
Pepsi Bottling Group Inc., rose $1.063 to $29.938
</P>
<P>
   The bottler of Pepsi soft drinks reported second-quarter
earnings of 58 cents a share from profits from operations, up from
32 cents a share a year ago.
</P>
<P>
J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co., rose $1.562 to $124.125
</P>
<P>
   The investment bank reported second-quarter earnings of $2.90 a
share, up from $2.52 cents a year ago. Wall Street analysts had
predicted the company's earnings would decline to $2.45 last
quarter.
</P>
<P>
NASDAQ
</P>
<P>
Ariba Inc., rose $27.688 to $131.188
</P>
<P>
   The Internet software company reported narrower than expected
fiscal third-quarter losses and said it will be profitable within a
year. In addition, its alliance with International Business
Machines Corp. and i2 Technologies Inc. was selected to build a
planned Internet commerce marketplace called WorldWide Retail
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
PMC-Sierra Inc., rose $20.875 to $228.938
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian semiconductor company agreed to buy Quantum Effect
Devices Inc., Santa Clara, Calif., for $2.14 billion in stock, the
latest in a series of acquisitions that have helped the company
expand operations.
</P>
<P>
Redback Networks Inc., rose $7.125 to $163.625
</P>
<P>
   The phone-equipment maker said second-quarter sales quadrupled,
rising to $48.7 million from $11.1 million.
</P>
<P>
Tollgrade Communications Inc., rose $28.047 to $166.297
</P>
<P>
   The phone equipment maker reported second-quarter earnings of 54
cents a share, well above Wall Street analysts estimates of
31-cents a share.
</P>
