<HEADLINE> Well-known artifact shop damaged in partial building collapse  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS OLERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Two floors collapsed Thursday at a lower
Manhattan architectural salvage shop specializing in period pieces
for movie sets and residential renovations.
</P>
<P>
   One person, a construction worker, suffered bruises; nine others
escaped injury, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, two brownstones collapsed in Brooklyn's Boerum
Hill neighborhood, killing three residents. Investigators were
still trying to determine on Thursday whether a gas explosion was
to blame.
</P>
<P>
   The four-story Lower East Side building, home to Irreplaceable
Artifacts, was undergoing some sort of construction, Giuliani said.
But he said building officials were searching for work permits.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are no permits for construction that we've been able to
find quickly,'' Giuliani later told a City Hall news conference.
''A lot of the bricks that fell are new bricks ... and this is a
building that dates from the 19th Century.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also said the building had code violations in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Commissioner Thomas Von Essen said ''there was very, very
heavy stuff'' on a floor that collapsed. He added that some floors
had been shored up after a fire 1&AMP;frac12; years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse left a gaping 2&AMP;frac12;-story hole in the structure,
leaving a clear view of the crumpled and twisted interior. The
fourth floor appeared to be intact.
</P>
<P>
   Von Essen said the remains of the building were in ''a very
dangerous condition.'' Nine families from a seven-story apartment
building next door were relocated.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse temporarily disrupted service on the subway's F
line. Trains were running, but bypassing that stop.
</P>
<P>
   Irreplaceable Artifacts sells architectural pieces, including
wooden doors, mantles, railings and elaborate moldings, from
buildings torn down around the city. Owned by Evan Blum, its
memorabilia has turned up in ''Angel Heart,'' starring Robert
DeNiro and Mickey Rourke; ''Sophie's Choice;'' and Woody Allen's
''Zelig.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
