<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President-Elect Fox Plans Advisors  </HEADLINE>
By NIKO PRICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's president-elect said Thursday he
will create a close-knit team of seven advisers who will ''demand
results in the name of the president'' and oversee the major
changes he plans after 71 years of single-party rule.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with foreign journalists, Vicente Fox described a
governing style very different from that of the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, which has held the presidency since
1929. Under the PRI, the president had sweeping authority, and most
orders came directly from him.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said he would delegate much of his work after he is sworn in
on Dec. 1, creating a new level of czars between him and the
Cabinet that would answer directly to him, and would spur his
Cabinet members to meet goals.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the czars will handle a specific theme: corruption,
poverty, Indians, small loans, the economy, education and social
development.
</P>
<P>
   ''They will have very small staffs,'' he said. ''They will go to
the secretariats to recommend plans, give them suggestions and
demand results in the name of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox has hired several headhunting firms to scour Mexico -- and
Mexicans in the United States -- for talent that could work in his
government. He pledged to interview the top three candidates for
each post personally, forming his government in two months.
</P>
<P>
   ''If in those two months I can form a team that is professional,
talented, executive, globally competitive, serious, honest and
transparent, I certainly won't spend much time in the office. I'll
leave the work to them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would travel constantly around Mexico, talking to
people from all backgrounds to get a better idea of what people
want and how the government is responding to their needs. He said
he would meet weekly with his Cabinet to map out the week's
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also said he considers it urgent to begin meetings with
other parties in an attempt to draft a multiparty plan for
political, economic and social reform. He wants to meet with the
two main presidential candidates he defeated within two weeks to
get them on board.
</P>
<P>
   But he conceded that the PRI and the leftist opposition, which
is also trying to reinvent itself after Fox's stunning victory,
will probably reject his overtures to ally with him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see that as a very possible reality,'' he said. ''Whoever is
governing, the other two parties tend to oppose him.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said if that happens, he will seek out members of Congress
from the other parties and try to win them over one by one.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without an agreement, we'll have to govern with whatever we
can get,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's party doesn't have a majority in either house of Congress,
and the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, still holds 21
of Mexico's 31 governorships.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said he plans to travel to South America -- Brazil, Argentina
and Chile, and possibly another country -- in the first half of
August, and to Washington to meet with President Clinton in the
second half of August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
