<HEADLINE> SEC Employees Vote on Union  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A union spokesman said turnout was heavy
Thursday among employees of the Securities and Exchange Commission
in a vote on whether to join the National Treasury Employees Union.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout has been ''great,'' spokesman Jim Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   The vote has been opposed for months by SEC officials, who
wanted employees at the Washington headquarters to be represented
by a separate bargaining unit from those in the agency's regional
offices around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute delayed a vote first scheduled for last September by
SEC employees on joining the NTEU, which represents about 155,000
workers in 26 federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Labor Relations Authority ruled against the SEC in
January. The SEC appealed the ruling; its appeal was rejected this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   The union needs to get a simple majority of votes cast to become
the SEC employees' official representative to negotiate with
management. NTEU officials have said they were confident, although
there appears to be far less support for the union among the SEC's
1,200 or so professional employees, mainly attorneys and
accountants, than from the 650 other employees who are eligible to
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Professional employees also are voting on whether to join the
same bargaining unit as their non-professional colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Employees have complained that they are expected to work
uncompensated extra hours, known as ''donated'' time, and that
bonus money is seldom given to career employees.
</P>
<P>
   The NTEU represents employees at the Internal Revenue Service,
the U.S. Customs Service, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. and
the Food and Drug Administration, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Treasury Employees Union: http://www.nteu.org
</P>
<P>
   Securities and Exchange Commission: http://www.sec.gov
</P>
<P>
   (gordon)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
