<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Rise on Earnings Reports  </HEADLINE>
By DUNSTAN PRIAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed higher Thursday as investors took
a cautious but mostly optimistic view of another batch of strong
second-quarter earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 5.30 at 10,788.71.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also closed higher. The Nasdaq
composite index finished up 75.27 at 4,174.86 and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 2.92 to 1,495.84.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors traded cautiously in the wake of a
strong rally Wednesday, which many believe was a so-called
technical rally, or one in which stocks rise temporarily despite
broader trends that indicate stocks may be in a long-term slump.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, investor optimism has been fed by strong earnings
in several key sectors, including technology and financial
services.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, investors have apparently taken temporary comfort
in the fact that fuel costs appear to have stabilized, as well as a
general belief that the Federal Reserve Board may be finished
raising interest rates for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   ''But it's earnings that continue to be the driving force,''
said Ricky Harrington, technical analyst with Wachovia Securities
in Charlotte, N.C., said. ''The market, temporarily at least,
doesn't appear to be concerned with interest rates or energy
prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington said that optimism could be tested Friday, when the
Producer Price Index figures for June are released. The PPI, which
measures producers' costs for making goods, is used widely as a
barometer of inflation because if producers' costs are rising,
those costs will ultimately be passed on to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Strong earnings reports helped the technology sector advance for
a second straight session Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The surge was led by Ariba, which closed up $27.688 to $131.188.
The Internet software company reported narrower than expected
fiscal third-quarter losses and said it will be profitable within a
year. In addition, its alliance with International Business
Machines and i2 Technologies was selected to build a planned
Internet commerce marketplace called WorldWide Retail Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Semiconductor stocks also flourished. Applied Micro Circuits was
up $28.062 to $153.50, and PMC-Sierra rose $20.875 to $228.938.
</P>
<P>
   And cellular phone maker Motorola jumped $4 to $39.50 after
announcing that its second-quarter earnings will match Wall
Street's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But Yahoo!, whose better-than-expected earnings served as the
catalyst for Wednesday's rally, finished down $2.375 to $122.563 as
some investors took profits.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan rose $1.562 to $124.125 after the investment bank
reported second-quarter earnings of $2.90 a share, up from $2.52
cents a year ago. Wall Street analysts had predicted the company's
earnings would decline to $2.45 last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence of the cautious environment, many so-called old
economy stocks fared poorly Thursday. For example, General Electric
reported solid earnings but its shares closed down $1.125 to
$52.375. Drug companies also suffered. Bristol Myers Squibb fell
$3.078 to $52.922 and Merck declined $4.344 to $69.047.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues were slightly ahead of decliners on the New
York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 1.02 billion shares, up
from Wednesday's pace of 994.63 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 2.51 at 542.76.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.76 percent.
Germany's DAX index was up 1.84 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
down 0.66 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 0.52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
