<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two shore towns adopt underage drinking measures  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   AVALON, N.J. (AP) - Beach communities eager to crack down on
underage drinking have a new tool, and they are wasting no time
using it.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by a new law, borough councils in Avalon and Surf City
voted Wednesday to enact ordinances banning the possession of
alcohol in private by minors. Ship Bottom is expected to follow
suit next week.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, people under 21 could not be charged if caught
drinking or possessing alcohol in private.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, Gov. Christie Whitman signed into law a measure
that gives municipalities the power to fine and suspend the
driver's license of any minor caught possessing alcohol in private.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, violators are subject to a $200 fine for the first
offense and a $350 fine for subsequent offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The law is aimed at shore town ''animal houses'' where teens
party during the summer, according to its sponsor, state Sen.
Leonard Connors, R-Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Exceptions will be made for minors who work where alcohol is
present and those participating in religious services.
</P>
<P>
   Connors said police won't be looking in windows to prosecute
minors. But if they are called to a home for another reason - such
as noise - and learn minors have alcohol in the house, summonses
can be issued.
</P>
<P>
   In Avalon, the underage drinking ordinance marks the latest
effort to clamp down on rowdy summer behavior. In 1997, police
began enforcing an ordinance that banned minors from being ''in the
presence of alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 500 people were arrested over the July Fourth weekend
that year. But the arrests triggered a federal court case that said
police did not have probable cause to enter premises for the
arrests, and the borough ended up paying $1.5 million in a
settlement and repealing its ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   In Surf City, nine of every 10 noise complaints received by
police in summer are associated with underage drinking, according
to police Lt. Martin McNulty.
</P>
<P>
   Others municipalities are considering enacting similar
ordinances, Connors said. He said the threat of loss of license
will be a deterrent for some - not all - minors who drink.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the most prized things young adults have is a driver's
license,'' said Connors. ''They're going to get the message.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-13-00 1724 </TRAILER>
