<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Photo pursuing  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - A tourist destination wouldn't normally tout
the fact that it has sharks, but that's just what Camden did
Thursday, in announcing the name of the city's new minor-league
baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   The Camden Riversharks of the Atlantic League will begin play in
the spring of 2001. A 6,425-seat stadium is being built on the
waterfront and is scheduled to be ready by early May, ''weather
permitting,'' said team owner Steve Shilling.
</P>
<P>
   The team logo features a gray shark baring its teeth as it cuts
through a light blue and navy wave. A white baseball with red
stitching is the backdrop. The logo will appear on T-shirts, golf
shirts and caps. Fans already began buying the clothing at
Thursday's event at the Camden Children's Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now we have an identity,'' General Manager John Brandt said.
''People will know who we are. And our name and logo reflect not
only our pride in being located in Camden, but also our pride in
being part of the revitalization effort along the city's
waterfront.''
</P>
<P>
   City school children chose the team name in a contest in the
spring. More than 10,000 students in kindergarten through eighth
grade voted from seven choices. (The others were the Batts,
Cowfish, Craze, Crickets, Rivermen and Waterdogs.)
</P>
<P>
   The school that had the highest percentage of voter
participation will receive $10,000 from the baseball team to be
used for athletic equipment. All of the students who voted for the
winning name will get two free tickets to a home game during the
opening season.
</P>
<P>
   The team will play 70 home games and 70 road games per season.
The league is comprised of minor league players and those from
college and semipro ranks. The Atlantic City Surf, Newark Bears and
Somerset Patriots play in the league. The league also has teams in
Bridgeport, Conn.; Lehigh Valley, Pa.; Long Island, N.Y.; Aberdeen,
Md.; and Nashua, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium, on Delaware Avenue at the foot of the Benjamin
Franklin Bridge, will have 19 suites, a restaurant, picnic area and
children's play area. It will be owned by Rutgers University-Camden
and also will be home to the school's team. The firm Camden
Baseball LLC will lease and operate the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Shilling has said the stadium will create 270 jobs on game days.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.camdenbaseball.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-13-00 1734 </TRAILER>
