<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Awaits Gore Probe Information  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno said Thursday she
wants to assess the views of a number of aides before deciding
whether to appoint a special counsel to investigate Vice President
Al Gore's role in the 1996 campaign fund-raising scandal.
</P>
<P>
   At her weekly news briefing for reporters, Reno said she
received the written recommendation of task force chief Robert
Conrad on Tuesday. Conrad favors appointing a special counsel to
probe whether Gore lied about his knowledge of fund-raising
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to consider anything that anybody wants to present, so
I'm awaiting ... the recommendation of others,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 and 1998, top Justice Department officials weighed in
with opinions on whether an outside prosecutor was needed to probe
Gore and both times Reno rejected such a move.
</P>
<P>
   Reno offered no specific time for her decision.
</P>
<P>
   Reno also said ''I am not commenting'' on whether an
investigation had been concluded -- or had even been undertaken --
into who leaked word of Conrad's verbal recommendation for a Gore
probe several weeks ago to Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to keep the focus on the Gore fund-raising questions,
House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., announced a
hearing next Thursday on banning soft money solicitations on
federal property.
</P>
<P>
   It is illegal to solicit campaign money on federal property.
Gore made calls from the White House but maintains he was raising
only ''soft money'' -- unlimited donations that corporations, labor
unions and some individuals give to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money solicitation is exempt from the election laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-13-00 1754 </TRAILER>
