<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals court judges critical of Volpe's appeal  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Federal appeals court judges Thursday rejected a
lawyer's suggestion that former police officer Justin Volpe did not
plan to sexually assault Abner Louima.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't think there was a planned sexual assault when they
went into the bathroom?'' Judge John M. Walker Jr. of the 2nd U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals asked during arguments about the legality
of the 30-year prison term given Volpe.
</P>
<P>
   ''No I do not your honor,'' responded Volpe's attorney, Alan
Chaset of Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ''What did he have the stick for?'' the judge asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think he knew what he had the stick for,'' Chaset
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh c'mon,'' Walker said, interrupting the lawyer who was
trying to convince the judges that U.S. District Court Judge Eugene
Nickerson in Brooklyn had sentenced Volpe too harshly for
sodomizing Louima with a broken broomstick on Aug. 9, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Chaset said Nickerson misinterpreted federal sentencing
guidelines, unfairly penalizing his client multiple times for the
same offenses and failing to credit him for naming the other
officer in the bathroom during the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe pleaded guilty in the middle of his trial last year. He
arrested Louima after mistaking the 30-year-old security guard for
someone who punched him in the head as police tried to break up an
unruly crowd outside a Brooklyn nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Sonia Sotomayor warned Chaset early in Thursday's
proceeding that it might be dangerous to argue Volpe's sentence was
excessive rather than merely challenging Nickerson's legal
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ''What happens when we think the sentence imposed is too lenient
and not sufficient for the act committed?'' Sotomayor asked Chaset,
suggesting that the appeals court might actually seek to increase
the prison term if it decided the case based on the brutality of
the crime.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, Chaset said Volpe might not have sodomized
Louima if he had not encountered the defendant at the front desk
with his pants down.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really think your argument should not try to exonerate the
seriousness of this crime and what Mr. Volpe did by somehow arguing
that he's less than morally culpable,'' Walker said. ''That's just
not going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   ''When they went into the bathroom, it's a fair inference they
did so, and Mr. Volpe did so, with the ultimate outcome firmly in
mind,'' Walker said. ''It wasn't a spontaneous act on his part.''
</P>
<P>
   Sotomayor agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''He goes to another room, finds the broomstick, breaks it ...
hides one end of it and brings another to the bathroom and then
gets Mr. Louima. How can't it be premeditated that he intended to
do something with that stick and it was not something nice,''
Sotomayor asked.
</P>
<P>
   Chaset said Volpe might have planned to hit Louima with the
stick or threaten him with it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there is any specific evidence we can point to
that says the intent, the plan, was to commit the assault that was
eventually committed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chaset said outside court that the best he could hope for was to
reduce Volpe's sentence by half if the appeals court agreed with
his legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   The court reserved decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
