<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CRDA grant completes funding to rehabilitate Paulsdale  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MOUNT LAUREL, N.J. (AP) - A group planning to renovate the
birthplace of Quaker suffragist Alice Paul can begin work, now that
the final funding has been granted.
</P>
<P>
   The Casino Reinvestment Development Authority has contributed
$328,000 for renovation of Paulsdale, Paul's Mount Laurel
birthplace, the agency announced Thursday. The funds were provided
by Bally's Park Place Casino Resort.
</P>
<P>
   The money will be used to complete a match required by the New
Jersey Historic Trust, which granted $478,000 to the Alice Paul
Centennial Foundation in 1998 for the restoration project. Last
year, the foundation received $150,000 in matching funds from the
Heritage Investment Program funded by the Pew Charitable Trusts.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is working to enhance public awareness of Paul's
life and work. The group acquired Paulsdale in 1990 and has worked
to complete the purchase of the property, to raise funds to restore
the house and grounds and to develop Paulsdale as a leadership
development center for women and girls.
</P>
<P>
   With the rehabilitation of Paulsdale, 6 1/2 acres of open space
in Burlington County will be preserved. The site will be part of
the New Jersey Women's Heritage Trail, which is being developed.
</P>
<P>
   Paul was born in Paulsdale in 1885. A radical suffragette, she
campaigned to win women the right to vote and authored the first
Equal Rights amendment. She died in a Moorestown nursing home in
1977 at age 92.
</P>
<P>
   Paulsdale, a three-story 19th century white farmhouse, was
designated a National Historic Landmark by the U.S. Department of
the Interior in 1991. Last year, the site was recognized by the
President's Commission on the Celebration of Women in American
History as one of six historic sites nationwide whose leaders were
''saving American treasures.'' It also was named by the National
Trust for Historic Preservation as an official Save America's
Treasures Project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
