<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer: Harris' hands will not be shackled in death row stomping trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) - Death row inmate Ambrose Harris will wear
shackles around his ankles but his hands will be free during an
upcoming trial, according to a published report.
</P>
<P>
   Harris is accused of stomping to death fellow death row inmate
Robert ''Mudman'' Simon on Sept. 7, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers filed a motion asking that Harris be unshackled
when he meets with them at the prison. Prosecutors filed a
competing motion asking that Harris not only continue to wear
shackles around his hands and feet during those meetings, but also
during his trial.
</P>
<P>
   They argued the shackles are needed to protect guards and others
in the courtroom against any violent outburst. State Superior Court
Judge Paul F. Chaiet said he would make the decision if the two
sides could not come to an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' attorney James Barletti told The Times of Trenton in
Thursday's edition that the defense counsel and the prosecutors
agreed that his client would wear only leg irons.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Prosecutor Thomas Meidt told the newspaper he would
not comment on the agreement until the judge approves the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Barletti said he is pleased with the decision to uncuff his
client.
</P>
<P>
   ''His defense is going to be one where he needs to describe what
took place and, if possible, show us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, 48, is awaiting a date with the executioner for the 1992
carjack, rape and murder of 22-year-old Kristin Huggins of Lower
Makefield, Pa. That conviction remains on appeal but has been
upheld by the state Supreme Court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
