<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retired bank manager wins $15 million verdict for botched brain surgery </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Manhattan jury awarded a retired bank manager
$15 million Thursday for brain damage he received when surgeons
blocked blood flow through an artery in his head and caused him to
have a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   The jury awarded the money to Jose Vigo, 54, who underwent
neurosurgery at New York Hospital in April 1995 to have a benign
tumor removed from the right temporal lobe of his brain and to stop
his epileptic seizures.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel C. Minc, Vigo's lawyer, contended that Dr. Richard A.
Fraser accidentally cauterized a major blood vessel in the right
temple, thereby stopping flow to extensive areas of the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Vigo suffered paralysis of the left side as well as visual
impairment in both eyes. He now uses a cane and leg brace to walk
and his left arm is useless, Minc said.
</P>
<P>
   Vigo's lawsuit, filed in Manhattan's State Supreme Court in
1996, named New York Hospital and Fraser as defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants' lawyer, George Van Setter, could not be reached
for comment. Minc said Van Setter had argued that only a minor
branch of the blood vessel, called the anterior choroidal artery,
was cauterized and that the damage to the arterial branch caused a
clot obstruction in the main artery - an acceptable risk in the
kind of surgery Vigo underwent.
</P>
<P>
   After a four-week trial, the jury apparently rejected that
argument and awarded Vigo $2 million for past pain and suffering
and $13 million for future problems.
</P>
<P>
   Vigo, who came to this country from Cuba in the mid 1970s, lives
on the Upper West Side and is a former manager of Exte Bank in
Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
