<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN: No Sahara Referendum Progress  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United Nations said Thursday there has
been no progress in a dispute over who an independence referendum
for Western Sahara, suggesting that some alternative to the vote
might need to be considered.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan said in a report to the Security
Council that negotiations on the referendum had actually moved
''backwards'' after the last round of talks between Morocco and
Western Sahara's independence-seeking rebels, held in London on
June 28.
</P>
<P>
   During those talks, which were headed by former U.S. Secretary
of State James Baker III acting as Annan's personal envoy, neither
side offered proposals to resolve their differences, which have
delayed the referendum for nearly 10 years, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They both insisted on a 'winner-take-all' approach and did not
appear willing to discuss a solution where each would get some, but
not all, of what each wanted,'' Annan wrote.
</P>
<P>
   War broke out in the Western Sahara in 1976, after Spain
abandoned the territory and Morocco annexed it, moving in settlers.
</P>
<P>
   About 15,000 guerrilla fighters from the rebel Polisario Front
battled Morocco's U.S.-equipped army until 1991, when the war ended
with a U.N.-negotiated cease-fire and plans to hold a referendum to
either remain part of Morocco or become independent.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum, however, has been stalled for years because of
disagreements over who is eligible to vote. The Polisario claims
Morocco has tried to pad the voter lists with people who have no
right to have a say in the territory's future.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has been registering voters, but tens of
thousands of people -- most of them based in Morocco -- have appealed
the rulings that they weren't eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the continuing divisions, Baker suggested possible
alternatives to a referendum during the London meeting, such as a
negotiated agreement for Western Sahara's full integration with
Morocco, full independence or something in between if the two sides
couldn't reach a final agreement on holding the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Annan repeated those options in his report. It was believed to
be the first time that the United Nations has publicly suggested
some other alternative to the referendum -- but it wasn't at all
clear that any of those options would be palatable to the two
sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
