<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trinidad testifies for accused IBF founder  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Longtime IBF welterweight champion Felix
Trinidad testified Thursday that he never made payoffs, or had
anyone make payoffs, to ensure good treatment by the IBF.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad, called as a defense witness, said he relinquished his
IBF belt because he could no longer stay under 147 pounds for
welterweights.
</P>
<P>
   He now fights as a junior middleweight, which has a limit of
154, and holds the WBA title in that division.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors accuse IBF founder Robert W. Lee and other IBF
officials of taking $338,000 from promoters and managers in a span
of more than a decade in exchange for favors and rigged rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors call Trinidad promoter Don King an unindicted
coconspirator, maintaining King was the prime beneficiary of Lee's
manipulations.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad (37-0, 30 knockouts) has not figured in payoffs
described in court.
</P>
<P>
   He said he knew Lee, but was not familiar with C. Douglas
Beavers, the former chairman of the IBF ratings committee who
became a government informant.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad said he did not know who did the ratings for the East
Orange-based IBF, one of the sport's three major governing bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, all of them must have a high opinion of me because I'm a
great fighter, great boxer,'' Trinidad said.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers has testified that the IBF ratings were compiled by Lee
and himself, contrary to the group's rules, which call for the
ratings committee to do the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Summations in the trial, which began in mid-April, are scheduled
to begin next week.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 66, of Fanwood, N.J., and his son, Robert Jr., 38, of
Scotch Plains, N.J., are both defendants. They face multiyear
prison terms if convicted of conspiracy, racketeering, fraud and
tax charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
