<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colonel sentenced to five months in jail for role in wife's drug scheme </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Lamenting a national ''betrayal,'' a federal
judge sentenced the former commander of the military's anti-drug
operation in Colombia to five months in prison for laundering cash
from his wife's drug deals.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence in Brooklyn federal court Thursday by U.S. District
Judge Edward Korman surprised the defendant, Col. James Hiett, and
even prosecutors, who chose not to oppose his bid for probation.
Hiett's attorney had argued he deserved a break because of his
spotless 24-year military record, and because - with his wife
jailed - he is raising two sons alone.
</P>
<P>
   But Korman called Hiett's crime a ''betrayal of trust'' in the
War on Drugs, and scolded the defendant - initially for declining
to speak in court, then for not showing more remorse when he did.
</P>
<P>
   When an offender ''is in a position of trust, when someone is a
colonel in Colombia ... it undermines confidence in the military,
it undermines confidence in the country's drug program,'' Korman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hiett, 48, who has filed for retirement from the Army, pleaded
guilty in April to charges he failed to turn his cocaine-addicted
wife for a trafficking scheme in which she shipped drugs from a
post office in the U.S. embassy in Bogota to New York City. He
admitted trying to launder $25,000 in proceeds - using some to pay
bills - after he learned the Army was investigating.
</P>
<P>
   ''Can I ask you something, colonel?'' Korman said at one point,
dropping his head and rubbing his brow. ''How is it you have
nothing to say?''
</P>
<P>
   Hiett finally told the judge that prosecutors' statements that
he brought ''dishonor to myself and the military are entirely
accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ''The only thing I did, that I did consciously,
was to try to protect my wife after the fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Korman later told Hiett's attorney, Abraham Klott, that he was
''taken aback when he didn't say, 'I'm sorry.'''
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move, the judge allowed the mother of an Army
pilot who died earlier this year on a spying mission in Colombia to
stand and demand a harsh sentence for Hiett. The family of the
pilot, Jennifer Odom, alleges Hiett has withheld information about
the crash of her plane, which the Army labeled an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Odom ''had no idea she was serving under someone who was sending
back drugs to the United States while she was going out on
anti-drug missions,'' said the mother, Janie Shafer.
</P>
<P>
   After Klott complained about the remarks, Korman insisted he did
not believe Hiett ''had anything to do with (Odom's) death, and I
am not taking that into account.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiett was ordered to surrender on Jan. 8, 2001. Once released
from prison, he will be under house arrest for five months as part
of a year's probation.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Laurie Hiett pleaded guilty to drug conspiracy
charges, admitting she shipped packages containing $700,000 worth
of heroin and cocaine. She is serving a five-year sentence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
