<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal judge says Boy Scouts eligible for payroll deduction  </HEADLINE>
dtfons
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - Bolstered by last month's U.S. Supreme
Court ruling that gives the Boy Scouts of America the right to ban
gay troop leaders, the group will once again be able solicit
charitable contributions from a state employee payroll program.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ruled Thursday that the Boy Scouts must be
included on a list of state employee charity payroll deductions,
despite a state agency's determination that the groups' hiring
policies violated state discrimination laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Boys Scouts were dropped from the payroll program after the
Commission on Human Rights and Opportunities ruled in May that the
Scouts' hiring policies were discriminatory
</P>
<P>
   The Scouts appealed the ruling and also filed a federal
discrimination lawsuit against the state.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the lawsuit, U.S. District Court Judge Warren
Eginton said he will sign an order directing the Connecticut State
Employee Campaign Committee to return the Boy Scouts to the list
for the rest of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's decision comes about a month after the U.S. Supreme
Court ruled that the Boy Scouts have the right to ban gay leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was the right thing to do, especially in light of the
Supreme Court's recognition that the Boy Scouts have a first
amendment right to their membership policies,'' said Daniel L.
Schwartz, the lawyer who filed the lawsuit for the Boy Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Boy Scouts brought this action so that they could remain
in the state employee campaign, as they have participated in the
campaign for the last 30 years,'' Schwartz said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1999 campaign, $9,950 was contributed directly to the Boy
Scouts by state employees. The Scouts also received a portion of
$200,000 in non-designated contributions. The Scouts were line to
receive just over $10,000 this year, according to payroll campaign
documents.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Richard Blumenthal, who represents the
state in the lawsuit, was still reviewing the ruling Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have any comment,'' said Blumenthal. ''We're
reviewing the order and advising the CHRO and the state employee
campaign as to what it means.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the state employee campaign could not be reached
for comment. Phone calls seeking comment from Janice Gwudz,
director of the state employee campaign, were left on her office
voice mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
