<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Child critical after contracting E. coli during creek swim  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - A distraught mother and father's bedside
vigil neared the end of its second week Thursday as the source of
the E. coli bacteria that sickened their son continued to elude
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Seven-year-old Zachary See was in critical condition at
Children's Hospital in Buffalo, battling pneumonia as well as the
E. coli infection that shut down his kidneys, his grandmother, Sue
Richards, said.
</P>
<P>
   ''One day you can be running around playing,'' she said, ''and
the next day you're laying there dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Chautauqua County authorities believe the blonde, blue-eyed boy
contracted the bacteria while swimming in a creek in the Chautauqua
Gorge near the family's Westfield home, but they don't know how the
popular swimming hole became contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   E. coli is an intestinal bacteria often spread through animal or
human feces that gets into water supplies. It causes nausea,
diarrhea, cramps and in severe cases, kidney failure.
</P>
<P>
   There have been numerous instances where swimmers or bathers
contracted the illness. In August 1999, 37 people were sickened by
E. coli at Battle Ground Lake in Washington and several beaches
this year have been closed on Lake Erie and Lake Michigan because
of suspected E. coli contamination. At a Georgia water park in
1998, one girl died and dozens others were sickened by E. coli.
</P>
<P>
   In the Chautauqua County case, a wastewater treatment plant and
pumping station along the creek had been ruled out as sources,
Village Mayor Ron Catalano said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''(Crews) are out walking checking point sources to see if
there's been any kind of discharge,'' he said. Authorities are
investigating whether run-off from area farms may be to blame or
whether a beaver dam discovered in the creek could have played a
role.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just keep looking,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   David and Yvonne See, meanwhile, keep waiting for their son to
show signs of improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have not left his bedside for two weeks... I don't think
they've slept or eaten hardly at all,'' Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   Zachary was swimming with his 11-year-old brother during a
family outing at the creek July 1. Doctors believe he contracted
the bacteria through stitches he had received following recent
tooth surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Within a day, Zachary was suffering flu-like symptoms and was
hospitalized after blood tests revealed the E. coli.
</P>
<P>
   With hospital and household bills mounting, Richards said the
family is accepting donations at the Key Bank in Westfield. Her
son, David, is a car salesman. Yvonne See works as a cleaning
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ''They haven't been able to go to work. They have rent due,
utilities, car payments, car insurance,'' the grandmother said.
</P>
<P>
   Chautauqua County health officials advised swimmers to stick to
beaches where the water is regularly tested. Catalano acknowledged
it would be difficult to keep people from swimming in the gorge.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a beautiful place to go in the summertime,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-13-00 1843 </TRAILER>
