<HEADLINE> Giuliani chastises Con Ed for voltage dim in city  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A short circuit in a power line caused lights to
flicker across the city and Westchester County on Thursday and led
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to again question Con Edison's ability to
adequately supply the region with electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The voltage dip - which affected all of the utility's 3 million
customers - is the latest in a series of electrical glitches in the
city, including a brownout earlier this month on the Upper East
Side of Manhattan and a 19-hour blackout in Washington Heights last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was having lunch at the time and I saw the lights dim,''
Giuliani told a press conference. ''I thought it was twice, but
others said it was three times - and then Con Edison called us
after that and explained they were having a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani added: ''I don't know why lights have to blink off and
on in New York City. It would seem to me that (Con Ed) would have
enough notice, enough information to be able to make certain that
we have enough power.''
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison spokeswoman Joy Faber said the voltage dip occurred
about noon and was caused by a short circuit in an overhead
transmission line in Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   It was an ''isolated problem,'' Faber said.
</P>
</TEXT>
