<HEADLINE> Assembly passes school construction bill  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - All New Jersey schools will receive some
construction aid from the state under a multibillion dollar measure
passed Thursday by the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The 66-8 Assembly tally capped an ''extremely interesting
journey'' for the funding measure, as one lawmaker put it, and set
the stage for the state's largest public works program.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of Thursday's vote, schools across the state will
soon commence long-delayed projects to rebuild or replace crumbling
and overcrowded buildings, some more than a century old.
</P>
<P>
   The bill provides $6 billion for the state's 30 so-called
special needs districts and $2.6 billion for all other schools.
Counting interest, the program is expected to cost $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Projects in the poor schools will be funded at 100 percent, as
ordered by the state Supreme Court. Other schools will be
reimbursed at least 40 percent of the cost of projects.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman, who is expected to sign the bill within
10 days, said Thursday that most ground breakings probably won't
start until next summer because too much of the current
construction season has been lost. In its landmark 1998 ruling, the
court set a spring 2000 deadline for bill passage, but lawmakers
missed that by weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Work is already under way in 14 of the so-called special needs
districts for projects addressing health and safety concerns, the
governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said the measure is designed to help children in poor
and rich districts alike.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is about all children, in every district. It is about, for
the first time, having the state offer some financial support to
districts other than the (special needs) districts for capital
construction,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''And we know that there are classroom and school buildings
throughout the state that are in need of repair and renovation, so
I think it is only fair that we offer this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's bill was vastly different than the version first
introduced in the Assembly. Whitman changed it to appease members
of the Senate, who endorsed the amended version last month.
</P>
<P>
   ''This bill had an extremely interesting journey,'' said its
sponsor, Assemblyman Joseph Malone, R-Burlington.
</P>
<P>
   Some Assembly Republicans had balked at backing the bill after
Whitman stripped legislative veto power from it.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins said his promise Thursday to introduce a separate
bill creating a special legislative review panel helped change
enough minds to create a comfortable winning margin for the school
construction bill.
</P>
<P>
   However, the bill almost didn't win Collins backing.
</P>
<P>
   In a spirited speech from the floor of the Assembly, the speaker
admitted that he considered voting against it as a symbolic way to
register his displeasure with the court order.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the Supreme Court way overstretched,'' he said later.
''We don't need the court stepping in and being the Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   But Assemblyman Wilfredo Caraballo, D-Essex, argued that the
balance in power among the branches of government has not been
upended.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is exactly what the Founding Fathers had in mind: The
judicial branch has brought in a recalcitrant executive branch and
legislative branch and told them you've go to do the right thing,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Leonard Lance, R-Hunterdon, had other reservations.
He said he would rather the state adopt a pay-as-you-go approach on
school construction, thereby saving interest costs. If lawmakers
still insisted on borrowing the money, Lance said they ought to
first seek permission from the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers said they supported a flawed bill.
</P>
<P>
   For example, some complained the state's construction cost
allowance of $138 per square foot is too low for expensive northern
New Jersey cities.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not the perfect bill. It's not necessarily the best
bill. But it's the only bill before us,'' said Assembly Democratic
Leader Joseph V. Doria, D-Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   ''We find ourselves in a situation where the health, safety and
welfare of children is in jeopardy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also said they want to keep close tabs on the state
Economic Development Authority, the state agency charged with
managing the massive project for all the special needs districts,
plus all other districts that receive 55 percent or more of state
aid.
</P>
<P>
   David Sciarra, director of the Education Law Center, which sued
the state on behalf of poor school children, agreed that lawmakers
must follow through to ensure that the EDA and Department of
Education perform their new tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was the easy part, now the hard work begins,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins joked that as lawmakers were congratulating themselves,
one person, Education Commissioner David Hespe, may have spent
Thursday worrying about his new responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ''One person who has to be nervous today is poor David Hespe,''
Collins said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
