<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jets have everyone on hand for training camp  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY WILNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Al Groh's busy offseason is over. Now, the tough
part begins: coaching the New York Jets for real.
</P>
<P>
   Groh succeeds Bill Parcells, who merely took one of the NFL's
perennial underachievers and turned it into a contender. He doesn't
have defensive coordinator Bill Belichick on hand, either, and star
receiver Keyshawn Johnson now plays for Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   So as training camp begins Friday, is Groh ready?
</P>
<P>
   ''We've lost a legend, a genius and a star,'' Groh said, a
twinkle in his eye, a smile on his face and his tongue planted
firmly in his cheek. ''I don't know if we have a very good
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Groh is highly optimistic about the Jets, who come off
an 8-8 season in which they won their final four games and seven of
the last nine. They get back quarterback Vinny Testaverde, who
missed all but the first half of the 1999 season opener. They have
a star running back in Curtis Martin, a good, young offensive line
and some versatility at linebacker and in the secondary. Their
kicking games are solid.
</P>
<P>
   But there also are the holes, huge holes. No one was added to
the lineup who remotely resembles Johnson in the area of making big
plays at receiver. The new pass rushers are rookies - the top two
of an unprecedented four first-round draft picks were defensive end
Shaun Ellis and linebacker John Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end was a wasteland last year, and the likely starter also
is a rookie, first-rounder Anthony Becht.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not as if we're starting from scratch,'' Groh said. ''I
have high expectations of what we can accomplish in phases. It's a
cumulative and incremental thing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a clear picture of how I want the team to look, how it
plays, the manner of how it behaves. I want that collective mindset
that on the first weekend in September, we have the most team we
can have.''
</P>
<P>
   Groh has emphasized throughout the offseason training program
and in minicamps that he is not a Parcells clone. He understands he
has to establish himself as a head coach in the NFL; his only
previous experience in the job was at Wake Forest for six years in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ''That will be a part of it, I'm sure,'' Groh said. ''I'll coach
the team by being me and go from that point forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the challenges of his first training camp as head coach
will be finding kick returners after injured Leon Johnson was
released; establishing a deep passing game that will help the Jets
be more efficient inside the 20; and remaining aggressive on
defense.
</P>
<P>
   He believes all of those issues will be solved.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think all teams that are starting at this point have
expectations rather than confidence,'' Groh said. ''No one has
demonstrated performance at this point and confidence grows from
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ''Confidence is one of the most tenuous things in sports. It
comes and goes based on what players see happening on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Jets won't see on the field are, to use Groh's
sarcastic words, a legend, a genius and a star. That's a lot to
overcome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-13-00 1938 </TRAILER>
