<DOCNO> APW20000713.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former students accuse New Jersey rabbi of abuse over 20 years  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - For 30 years, Rabbi Baruch Lanner was known
in the Orthodox Jewish community as a charismatic, dynamic
educator, a founding principal of a yeshiva school in New Jersey
and guide on countless retreats.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues and students say Lanner would call parents to
persuade them to let their children travel to Israel with him,
board students at his Paramus home so they could attend yeshiva,
and inspire them to become better Jews. Some saw him as a
substitute father.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months, more than 25 former students have come
forward to say that for decades Lanner, a leader in the Orthodox
Union's National Conference of Synagogue Youth, also sexually,
physically and verbally abused them.
</P>
<P>
   The students, now in their 30s and 40s, said that Lanner kissed,
fondled and hit teen-age girls and kneed some boys in the groin.
His accusers also say he attacked a man with a knife.
</P>
<P>
   Lanner, 50, resigned as director of regions for the New
York-based youth group last month after The Jewish Week, a leading
Jewish weekly, published many of the allegations. Two New Jersey
prosecutors have begun criminal investigations and Lanner's
ex-employer, the Orthodox Union, has begun a probe to determine
whether it was responsible for covering up complaints about Lanner.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Yosef Blau, a Yeshiva University counselor and one of
Lanner's strongest critics, said the rabbi was largely protected by
the Orthodox Union, a venerable institution with a membership of
nearly 1,000 synagogues that also puts the seal of approval on
kosher food.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that they were so enamored with his success and
accomplishments that they didn't want to hear problems,'' Blau
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a code of loyalty here at the same time, and also he
was very scary,'' said Naomi Freistat, a 41-year-old doctor who
said that Lanner kissed and fondled her a dozen times and punched
her in the stomach when she was 15. ''This was a man where you
didn't know what was coming next.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanner lived in Paramus until separating recently from his wife
and now takes calls from a number in Fair Lawn. He said he has
violated Orthodox Jewish law in the past by having physical
relationships with former students - none teen-agers - but hasn't
broken any other laws.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did many things I shouldn't have done, but none of them were
illegal. None of them were perverted. None of them were
threatening,'' Lanner said.
</P>
<P>
   He denied most allegations printed in The Jewish Week and said
he couldn't recall others. He admitted accidentally kneeing a boy
in the groin in 1983 at the Monmouth County yeshiva he founded.
</P>
<P>
   He has never faced criminal charges, although a religious
tribunal was called in 1989 to investigate whether he had knifed a
Bergen County man suffering from cancer in an argument over who the
man should marry. Lanner was cleared.
</P>
<P>
   Bergen County prosecutors are investigating allegations in the
June 23 article, said First Assistant Prosecutor Fred Schwanwede.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, Marcie Lenk of Fort Lee, said that Lanner would make
frequent comments about her breast size and suggestively brush up
against her while she was a student in the early 1980s at the
Frisch School in Paramus.
</P>
<P>
   Lanner, who taught Talmud at the school, would say ''ooh, that
felt good,'' after brushing past her, Lenk, 34, told The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   Lanner said Lenk misinterpreted his actions. He said she stayed
at his home frequently and never spoke to him about feeling
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you felt threatened, idiot, why did you come?'' Lanner
said. ''Why did your parents let you come?''
</P>
<P>
   Lenk, who was 15 when she first came to the school, said she
stayed at Lanner's home about three times over three years. She
said Lanner manipulated many of his students into keeping quiet by
making them feel inferior. ''He made us believe that we needed
him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Monmouth County Prosecutor John Kaye is investigating the
complaint of a woman who said she was Lanner's student at the
Hillel school in Deal, which Lanner founded and was principal of
until 1997. Kaye said the woman came to Westfield police on Monday,
but wouldn't identify her or describe her complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The author of The Jewish Week article, editor and publisher Gary
Rosenblatt, said he spoke to between 15 and 18 people who
complained about Lanner for the article, and has received letters
from a dozen more since it was published.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of them didn't know there were any others,'' Rosenblatt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Freistat, a podiatrist in New York, told the AP that she met
Lanner when she traveled from Wilkes-Barre, Pa., to retreats in New
Jersey. Freistat said Lanner persuaded her mother to let her go on
his six-week trip to Israel in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Lanner asked Freistat to kiss him on the cheek the first week of
the trip, and on the second week summoned her outside - ''it was
always outside,'' she said - and kissed and fondled her. She
endured the contact a dozen times, she said, fearing that the youth
group leader would send her home.
</P>
<P>
   She said she tried to pull away the last time he approached her
in a Jerusalem courtyard near her hostel, and Lanner grabbed her.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said 'Don't walk away from me,''' Freistat said. ''He
punched me in the stomach. All I remember is just looking up at him
and saying 'You just punched the wrong girl.'''
</P>
<P>
   Freistat said she and another girl on the youth group spoke to
two rabbis, one who was helping lead the youth group tour, about
Lanner but the rabbi went unpunished. The Orthodox Union set up a
commission in June to find out ''who knew what and when did they
know it,'' said president Mandell I. Ganchrow.
</P>
<P>
   Freistat called the Union ''a boys' club,'' while other students
said that the organization let Lanner's conduct go unchecked
because he made a lot of money for it. Others said they were too
intimidated to speak out.
</P>
<P>
   Said Freistat: ''He was smart enough to pick on little kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
