<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chicken of the Sea settles trademark infringement case  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - Ask any trademark lawyer you happen to
see: Is the Mermaid Seafood company's mermaid too much like the
famous mermaid from ''Chicken of the Sea''?
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the two companies reached a settlement late
Thursday after fighting out a trademark infringement claim in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the settlement were not released.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over the two mermaids began in 1996 when lawyers for
Chicken of the Sea wrote to Mermaid Seafood and asked the company
to stop picturing or using the word ''mermaid'' in their name. The
Greenwich-based import-export company, which sells frozen cod,
salmon and haddock to wholesalers, began using a blue silhouette of
a mermaid on its packaging in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Chicken of the Sea has used its familiar smiling blonde mermaid
on its cans since 1952. The company's well-known jingle, ''Ask any
mermaid you happen to see, what's the best tuna? Chicken of the
Sea'' has been around since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Mermaid Seafood, however, said they had a right
to use their own mermaid. The company responded to Chicken of the
Sea's cease-and-desist letter by filing a federal lawsuit in
November 1996, asking the court to affirm its right to advertise,
sell and distribute frozen fish under its trademark and logo.
</P>
<P>
   The company also asked the court to stop Chicken of the Sea from
using a mermaid on its frozen seafood.
</P>
<P>
   But Chicken of the Sea filed a countersuit, calling its mermaid
trademark ''one of the most important and valuable assets'' of the
company.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, U.S. District Judge Alan Nevas began hearing
testimony on the issue of ''likelihood of confusion'' involving the
two companies' use of the two mermaids.
</P>
<P>
   But after two days of testimony, the two sides spent all day
Thursday negotiating behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   They emerged from the meetings at 6:30 p.m. and announced they
had reached a settlement. Citing a confidentiality agreement,
neither side would reveal any details, such as whether one company
is restrained from using the mermaid logo in any way or whether
there were monetary damages.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's settled. It's all confidential. We're all happy it's
over,'' said Susan Hollander, an attorney representing San
Diego-based Chicken of the Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Mussell, president and chief executive of Chicken of the
Sea, attended the trial, but would not comment on the settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-13-00 1941 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
