<HEADLINE> State changes course again on Hamilton building site  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman has found a new use
for a suburban Trenton site she abandoned for a state office
building.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of relocating the state Division of Revenue to the
Hamilton Township site, the governor announced Thursday that the
State Police will use the location to house its new Troop C
headquarters and communications center.
</P>
<P>
   The state will lose less than $1 million for changing course on
the project.
</P>
<P>
   The governor in April decided to maintain Division of Revenue
offices in Trenton instead of relocating them to Hamilton as first
planned. She did so to stem the loss of 500 jobs from Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, state officials estimated they had invested $3
million in the building site they were abandoning.
</P>
<P>
   More than $2 million worth of those site improvements can be
reused to house the State Police facility, state officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly members Gary Guear and Linda Greenstein, Democrats who
both represent the district that includes Hamilton, applauded the
news.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today's reversal by the governor corrects a wrong that should
never have been made,'' said Greenstein.
</P>
</TEXT>
