<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prudential, MetLife respond to lawsuits accusing them of discrimination </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Prudential Insurance Co. of America and MetLife
Inc. on Thursday defended themselves against allegations of racial
discrimination in the sale of insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to lawsuits, Prudential acknowledged that it had used
race-based underwriting in the distant past, and announced it is
establishing a toll-free telephone number for policyholders who may
have paid race-based premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Foley, a spokesman for the Manhattan-based Metropolitan
Life Insurance Co., said a lawsuit filed Tuesday in U.S. District
Court in New York was a ''very inaccurate and unjustified portrait
of our company.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit accused Met Life of charging black customers higher
premiums for less insurance coverage than it charged whites. It
also alleged that in 1920, the firm urged the construction of
mortality tables that would factor in race.
</P>
<P>
   It said Met Life, which calls itself the leading seller of life
insurance in the nation, began targeting mostly poor, black
customers eight decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Foley said the company doesn't engage in race-based
underwriting.
</P>
<P>
   ''No group of policyholders, including African Americans, have
suffered economic loss from doing business with our company,''
Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   A similar lawsuit was filed against Prudential in U.S. District
Court in Newark, N.J. Both lawsuits seek unspecified damages.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential issued a statement acknowledging it used race-based
underwriting in the past, but stopped in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ''While the practice of race-based underwriting is clearly
unacceptable by today's standards, Prudential acted in accordance
with what were then industry standard and generally accepted
actuarial and underwriting practices based on life expectancy,''
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob DeFillippo, a spokesman for the Newark-based company, said,
''The fact that race-based underwriting was used in the sale of
life insurance is very difficult for us to understand and
completely unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said some of the allegations against his company were
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits were brought by a group of law firms previously
involved in suing seven insurers who sold ''burial insurance''
policies to blacks clients mainly in the South.
</P>
<P>
   One of those companies, Houston-based American General Corp.,
agreed last month to pay more than $206 million to settle
allegations that black customers were charged higher premiums on
millions of policies.
</P>
<P>
   Barry A. Weprin, one of the lawyers who worked on the lawsuits,
laughed when he was told DeFillippo said establishing a toll-free
telephone number for ratepayers once subject to race-based premiums
was unrelated to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know how to respond to that. They didn't say it under
oath, I assume,'' Weprin said.
</P>
<P>
   DeFillippo said the toll-free telephone number was set up
because of increased public attention in general, including the
American General settlement, and because the Florida state
insurance department had made inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Prudential set up the following telephone number for anyone
who believes they might have paid race-based premiums for policies
purchased in the distant past: 1-800-201-7189.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-13-00 2004 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000713.0159 </DOCNO>
