<HEADLINE> Argentina Strike Strands Thousands  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Thousands of travelers were
stranded in the capital Thursday as a strike by bus Buenos Aires
drivers angry over a rash for dismissals stretched into a second
day.
</P>
<P>
   Travel was thwarted for some 40,000 people bound for Argentina's
interior and neighboring Paraguay and Bolivia, said Angel Giminez,
a Retiro bus station official in downtown Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
   A response to recent staff dismissals, the drivers launched the
strike after a local bus company announced some 400 workers were
being laid off, forcing hundreds of passengers to sleep upright in
chairs or sprawled on the floor Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The government called for an ''obligatory conciliation'' between
the company, La International, and the bus drivers union.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers insist they keep up the strike for an undetermined
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
