<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Torricelli works phones to pave way for possible Statehouse bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Democratic U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli is
paving the way for a possible run for New Jersey governor by making
early contacts with party leaders in various counties, according to
The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   The Times reported Thursday that Torricelli, D-N.J., has been
calling county and state party leaders and asking them their views
on his possible candidacy, and requesting they delay any promise to
back Woodbridge Mayor Jim McGreevey.
</P>
<P>
   One Democrat whom The Times did not identify said Torricelli has
been ''burning up the phones.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been reported in recent weeks that state party officials
have been calling Torricelli or encouraging him to run, but The
Times report is the first indication Torricelli is taking the
prospect seriously and doing something about it on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli spokeswoman Kristin Carvell said Torricelli was
unavailable for an interview Thursday and that his office had no
comment on The Times report.
</P>
<P>
   After winning a tough three-way primary in 1997, McGreevey
surprised New Jersey by giving Whitman a tough re-election fight,
losing by less than 28,000 votes. He was immediately seen as the
leading candidate for the Democratic nomination in 2001, although
one of his competitors in the 1997 primary, former Morris County
Prosecutor Michael Murphy, is expected to seek a primary rematch
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli had been a McGreevey ally and booster. Both were
closely but unofficially affiliated with Jon Corzine, the
high-spending winner of the June 6 Democratic primary for U.S.
Senate over former Gov. Jim Florio.
</P>
<P>
   But party officials remain worried about a rift between southern
and northern New Jersey Democrats that was exacerbated by the
Florio-Corzine fight and which would damage Democratic hopes of
recapturing the Statehouse when Whitman leaves. The Times reported
that some party officials are questioning whether McGreevey is up
to the job of reuniting north and south, suggesting Torricelli
would be a stronger candidate based in no small measure on his
lopsided U.S. Senate victory in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many leaders believe he would be the best candidate to run for
governor who could unite the party and heal its divisions, and to
avoid a divisive primary in the gubernatorial race,'' former
Torricelli chief of staff Jamie Fox told the newspaper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-13-00 2021 </TRAILER>
