<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Eyes Budget Deal With Clinton  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional Republicans said Thursday they
want to reach a quick compromise with President Clinton on the
year's biggest spending bill. The hope is to avoid a
campaign-season showdown over schools and other popular issues.
</P>
<P>
   In a closed-door meeting, House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.,
and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., told the chairmen
of the two chambers' appropriations committees to try striking a
deal with the White House next week, participants said. The
measure, which exceeds $340 billion, covers the Departments of
Education, Labor, and Health and Human Services for next year.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is perennially one of the last of the 13 spending bills
completed -- usually after the Oct. 1 start of the new fiscal year --
because it is a battlefield over education, workplace safety and
other highly politicized, difficult issues. Republicans are eager
to get those fights resolved before they can become a focus of the
November presidential and congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   House Appropriations Committee Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla. said
the instructions the leadership gave were ''to try to get what
would be a signable bill.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If we can get this bill to the president before the politics
starts, we'll have a working relationship'' with the White House
that could speed completion of the other spending bills, said his
Senate counterpart, Ted Stevens, R-Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Clinton has signed just one of the 13 spending bills for
fiscal 2001 into law.
</P>
<P>
   White House budget office spokeswoman Linda Ricci said
administration officials were ''always happy'' to meet with
lawmakers, but signaled that reaching a deal could be tough.
</P>
<P>
   Ricci said Clinton's ''key priorities'' for hiring teachers,
refurbishing schools and other issues would have to be met. She
also said Clinton wanted no policy changes that he opposes in the
bill and would want to ensure that the bill leaves enough money for
his proposals in later measures.
</P>
<P>
   ''Based on what we've seen to date, there's a long road to
travel,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has threatened to veto both the House- and Senate-passed
versions of the bill because of cuts in his proposals for teachers,
school repairs and social services grants to states. The bills
would also block planned administration regulations aimed at
reducing workplace injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats were jubilant when the GOP pushed the bill
through the House last month, saying its cuts would help Democrats
capture control of a chamber Republicans now govern with an 11-seat
majority. Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., top Democrat on the House
appropriations panel, said Thursday that even a quick deal with
Clinton on the bill would not change that.
</P>
<P>
   ''The politics has already been defined,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, House-Senate bargainers reached agreement on a
roughly $289 billion defense bill for 2001, about $20 billion more
than this year.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, about $4 billion higher than what Clinton proposed,
contains money for a 3.7 percent pay raise for military personnel.
It also has about $100 billion for procurement and for research and
development, Stevens said, amid complaints by Clinton that
lawmakers have added money for items the administration did not
request.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to House and Senate leaders, White House budget
chief Jack Lew said the administration ''opposes'' the defense
bill, but did not use the word ''veto.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-13-00 2022 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
