<DOCNO> APW20000713.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru Enacts Sweeping Phone Tap Law  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- A new law gives President Alberto Fujimori's
government sweeping powers to monitor private telephone calls,
Peru's largest telephone provider and opposition leaders charged
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, approved late Wednesday, gives Peru's
telecommunications watchdog agency, Osiptel much broader powers to
keep tabs on who's talking.
</P>
<P>
   ''From now on, the state, through Osiptel, can know who called,
with whom they spoke, when they spoke and from where they spoke,''
said Jorge Melo Vega, general manager of Regulations and Strategic
Planning for Telefonica del Peru.
</P>
<P>
   Melo Vega said Osiptel can now tap into confidential information
and company trade secrets, gaining access to data bases, software
and public phone records without a court order.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not only violating the rights of our company, but of
the entire sector,'' he told Radioprogramas del Peru.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation represents one of at least a dozen bills crafted
from ''urgent'' presidential decrees that Fujimori is trying to
push through Congress in its final session before he loses a clear
majority at the end of the month. The law does not give the
government free reign to eavesdrop on live telephone
communications.
</P>
<P>
   The measure comes amid growing accusations that he is
backpedaling on promises to fortify Peru's democracy and is
tightening his grip on power after his contentious May 28
re-election victory, which was marred by irregularities and
allegations of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ''It must be part of a strategy to penetrate communications,''
opposition Congressman Jorge del Castillo told The Associated
Press, adding that Fujimori must sign the law before it goes into
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Osiptel President Jorge Kunigami said Thursday that increased
powers will allow the agency to enforce regulations, levy fines and
promote competition in the telecommunications sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-13-00 2023 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
