<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elton John Performs in Liverpool  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIVERPOOL, England (AP) -- Elton John made a long-awaited return
to Liverpool Thursday with his first show there in 18 years, and
dedicated his performance to one of the city's most famous sons,
John Lennon.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Elton played a three hour set of ballads and rock and roll
anthems such as ''Daniel'' and ''Candle in the Wind'' to a crowd of
3,500.
</P>
<P>
   Opening the song ''Empty Garden'', written for Lennon, he said:
''I have played this song in New York and Hamburg but the most
fitting place and the only place to play it is here in Liverpool.''
</P>
<P>
   The 53-year-old star sat at his Yamaha piano wearing a single
breasted red satin lounge suit embroidered with pink flowers and
the word Medusa emblazoned in diamante stones across his back.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing the number ''Ticking,'' about the gun culture in the
United States, he told the crowd: ''This song was written back in
the 1970s ... it is a sad indictment on America that absolutely
nothing has changed since then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-13-00 2110 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000713.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assembly OKs transportation funding; presses case on improper spending </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - On one hand, the state Assembly settled one
$3.8-billion piece of business Thursday by approving a bill to fund
highway and rail projects through 2004.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the lower house opened a new can of worms on
how part of that $3.8 billion will be spent. It puts lawmakers on a
possible collision course with Gov. Christie Whitman over the use
of transportation project money to pay staff expenses they believe
should come out of her general budget instead.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation funding created something of a rift within the
Republican ranks this year as Senate President Donald DiFrancesco
developed a program that diverts revenue from state coffers and
uses it for projects to be financed and run by the Transportation
Trust Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Voters will be asked in November to change the state
constitution to permanently commit for transportation use revenues
from the wholesale petroleum tax and the sales tax on cars.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10.5-cent gasoline tax, 9 cents already goes to the Trust
Fund. Voters will be asked to dedicate the remaining 1.5 cents to
that purpose as well.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman originally opposed this diversion, saying it was OK this
year but could threaten the solvency of future state budgets. She
ultimately relented.
</P>
<P>
   But a new problem emerged when the Assembly inserted into the
Transportation Trust Fund bill new provisions to limit how much of
this ''project'' money could be spent on staff salaries,
maintenance and administrative costs.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than accept these limits, the governor in June vetoed the
$3.8 billion package and sent it back to the Legislature with her
amendments. The Senate agreed quickly but the Assembly delayed
action.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Assembly lawmakers Thursday reluctantly accepted
Whitman's version of a four-year program by a vote of 74-1.
</P>
<P>
   But they then promptly passed a second bill, A-2715, by a 70-2
vote to basically restore the part of the Trust Fund law that
Whitman had cut out. It passed with more than enough votes to force
an override if the governor is unwilling to meet them halfway.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly Transportation chairman, Alex DeCroce, R-Morris,
said Whitman was using too much of these project funds as a cash
source to help balance her budget.
</P>
<P>
   DeCroce said this was unforgivably foolish because it meant that
bond financing, with an interest charge and a 15- to 20-year
repayment schedule, was being used to cover weekly payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said Thursday it is customary for some staff costs to be
charged against a project. If a highway is being expanded, for
instance, engineers must design the layout and surveyors must
layout the site. Their pay for doing this work is folded into the
project's overall costs, just like the bulldozer and the salary of
the bulldozer driver.
</P>
<P>
   ''The concern here is that if the work is being done on a
project that is a TTF-related project in construction or design,
then that is legitimate, that is part of the total cost. Projects
don't just happen. They have to be designed, they have to have the
engineering work done,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's legitimate to be considered as part of the project
because the demands on general revenues become huge when you don't
do that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   What this means is that an engineer paid $75,000 for his year of
work on a Trust Fund project is being paid with borrowed money that
has to be repaid over 15 or 20 years. One way of looking at it is
the $75,000 salary will end up costing taxpayers more than $200,000
when interest is added. Another way is that taxpayers in 2020 will
be still paying for the salary that engineer earned this year.
</P>
<P>
   DeCroce agreed this is a customary practice - to a degree.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the Whitman administration has abused this, using
Trust Fund financing to pay as much as $200 million a year in
salary and administrative costs, and even for maintenance on old
Trust Fund projects, which is virtually every road or bridge built
or repaired by the state since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   DeCroce said many of these staff costs ought to be funded in
cash through the annual state budget for the Transportation
department. ''We are well over what we should be doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Trust Fund was meant to be a capital program which began
with capital improvements only,'' DeCroce said. ''What they are
attempting to do, in my opinion, is fund some of the
administration's costs through this bill.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trust Fund approved Thursday will spend between $900 million
and $950 million a year. DeCroce's clause would have capped the
salary and administrative spending at 14 percent this year, and
would have scaled it down to 10 percent by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman vetoed it, saying she could only accept a 13-percent cap
in future years and no cap at all this year.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins said this might be an issue on
which the Legislature will override a veto from Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very committed to having the Transportation Trust Fund
used just for capital projects and so forth,'' Collins said. ''We
were thinking very seriously (about it).''
--:
</P>
<P>
   Full text of the TTF bill, S-16, and of A-2715 are available at
the Office of Legislative Services Web site located at
http://www.njleg.state.nj.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-13-00 2112 </TRAILER>
