<DOCNO> APW20000713.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Circus will leave elephants home  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GLENS FALLS, N.Y. (AP) - Look for the lions and the tigers, the
Flying Wallendas' and the fire-eating sword swallower.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't come to the Circus Royale expecting to see elephants.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping out of the big top of big time attention focused on the
treatment of the big gray circus staples, Circus Royale President
Jim McConnell said he'll leave the elephants home when his show
rolls into town Sept. 28.
</P>
<P>
   The circus has also canceled the elephants' performances at all
but one other venue on its autumn tour.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've talked it through, and at this place and time, the issue
has to be resolved,'' McConnell told the Post-Star of Glens Falls.
''We're in the entertainment business, and it's in our interest to
entertain the public. The public has to arrive at their values. But
we know the animals are treated well. I can't stand to see animals
mistreated. But we'll still wait until the issue is resolved.'' The
issue of animal treatment has made to the national stage. In June,
U.S. Rep. Sam Farr, D-Calif., introduced a bill to outlaw use of
elephants in traveling shows and for rides. Hearings were held on
Capitol Hill to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearings, animal rights activists like ''The Price Is
Right'' host Bob Barker railed against the use of elephants,
calling it cruel and pointing out the 30 people killed by elephants
since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Circus advocates, though, maintain their animals are well cared
for and argue the fatalities are mostly handlers in one of the most
dangerous professions in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Glens Falls is 46 miles north of Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
