<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Orders Arrest of Ex-Pres.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- The Supreme Court on Thursday ordered the
arrest of ousted president Jamil Mahuad on charges of illegally
freezing bank accounts last year.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest order for Mahuad, who was toppled from power after a
military-backed Indian uprising on Jan. 21, was issued by Supreme
Court President Galo Pico, who also called for the arrest of former
Finance Minister Ana Lucia Armijos.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court is investigating charges that Mahuad and
Armijos exceeded their constitutional authority when they partially
froze private bank accounts in March 1999 in an attempt to save
Ecuador's collapsing financial system.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of depositors were told they would have to
wait a year before they could withdraw their money.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are indications that the commission of various crimes
were committed against constitutional guarantees and against public
administration,'' the arrest order said.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations stem from separate criminal complaints lodged by
Victor Granda, a socialist movement leader, and Congressman
Napoleon Gomez, of the conservative Social Christian party.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts have said if Mahuad and Armijos are convicted,
they could face up to five years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad's brother, Eduardo, said last week that the former
president is in the United States lecturing at Harvard. Local
newspaper reports said Armijos is in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   After the aborted military coup, Mahuad was replaced by his vice
president, Gustavo Noboa. The new president has largely carried on
with Mahuad's economic programs, including a plan to convert
Ecuador to an all-U.S. dollar economy.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was forced from office, Mahuad was widely condemned
for bailing out 18 failed banks last year at a cost of $1.2 billion
after the bankers stole the funds and fled abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-13-00 2211 </TRAILER>
