<DOCNO> APW20000713.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, July 13, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Philly Cops Decried Over Beating
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia mayor and the police department came
under fire today over the videotaped beating of a black man by a group of
officers. The U.S. Justice Department opened an investigation into whether
Thomas Jones' civil rights were violated, and black leaders decried the beating
as police brutality. A dozen officers -- black and white -- surrounded Jones,
30, as he was beaten and kicked on the street in the middle of the day
yesterday, moments after a stolen car chase and a shootout in which he and a
policeman were wounded. The beating was recorded from a TV news helicopter and
broadcast around the country.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ecuador Orders Arrest of Ex-President
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- The Supreme Court on Thursday ordered the arrest of
ousted president Jamil Mahuad on charges of illegally freezing bank accounts
last year. The arrest order for Mahuad, who was toppled from power after a
military-backed Indian uprising on Jan. 21, was issued by Supreme Court
President Galo Pico, who also called for the arrest of former Finance Minister
Ana Lucia Armijos. The Supreme Court is investigating charges that Mahuad and
Armijos exceeded their constitutional authority when they partially froze
private bank accounts in March 1999 in an attempt to save Ecuador's collapsing
financial system.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S.-Vietnam Trade Pact Signed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States and Vietnam signed a landmark trade
agreement today, marking what President Clinton hailed as ''another historic
step in the process of normalization, reconciliation and healing between our two
nations.'' It provides Vietnam with access to the world's largest market on the
same terms the United States grants to most other nations. The deal was signed
by U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky and Vietnam's Trade Minister Vu
Khoan. Vietnam agreed to sharply lower its tariffs and trade barriers on a wide
range of U.S.-manufactured products, farm goods and financial and other
services.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Teen Pregnancy on the Decline
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Extending a trend that began in the early 1990s, the teen-age
pregnancy rate in the United States fell 8 percent from 1995 to 1997, the
government said today. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said the
teen pregnancy rate -- the rate among girls 15 to 19 years old -- declined from
98.3 pregnancies per 1,000 girls in 1995 to 90.7 per 1,000 in 1997. In addition,
the pregnancy rate for girls under 15 declined 11 percent, from 7.2 per 1,000 to
6.4 per 1,000.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Gets Bradley's Endorsement
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Bill Bradley today endorsed Al Gore's Democratic
presidential bid four months after dropping out of their Campaign 2000 primary
fight. ''Winning is a team sport,'' Bradley said at a political rally. Gore
called Bradley ''a good Democrat who speaks and stands for principles we all
believe in.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Senate Mulls Inheritance Tax Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Republican bill to abolish federal inheritance taxes was
readied today for a final Senate vote despite a veto threat from President
Clinton and Democratic arguments that it would amount to a windfall for the
wealthy. Before the vote -- scheduled for tomorrow -- senators attached an
amendment to repeal the 3 percent telephone excise tax and defeated measures to
increase money available for a Medicare prescription drug benefit and to
temporarily suspend the federal gas tax. Republican supporters said the ''death
tax,'' which reaches a top rate of 55 percent, hinders investment and job
creation, forces millions of people to do costly estate planning and
particularly hurts farmers and small businesses.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Brazil To Strengthen Air Force
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- President Fernando Henrique Cardoso approved a $3
billion plan to modernize the country's aging air force, the defense minister
said Thursday. Geraldo Quintao said the air force will begin negotiations with
various aircraft manufacturers to get the best prices for the modernization of
100 Brazilian fighter jets and the purchase of 76 new patrol planes. Brazil's
long-neglected air force has been showing signs of serious fraying in recent
years.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose moderately Friday, partly lifted by an
overnight advance on Wall Street. The Nikkei Stock Average rose 52.21 points to
17,089.11 in early trading. In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average closed
up 5.30 at 10,788.71. The Nasdaq composite index finished up 75.27 at 4,174.86.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Braves 6, Orioles 3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Greg Maddux outpitched Mike Mussina and Bobby Bonilla
singled in the tiebreaking run in the seventh inning as the Atlanta Braves beat
Baltimore 6-3 tonight. Maddux (11-3) allowed three runs, eight hits and two
walks in seven innings to earn his second consecutive win after two straight
defeats.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-13-00 2300 </TRAILER>
