<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Plead Guilty in Attempted Bombing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RENO, Nev. (AP) -- Five white supremacists accused of an
attempted firebombing at a Jewish temple pleaded guilty the day
before they were to go to trial for the hate crime.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants, all in the late teens and 20s, were accused of
throwing a Molotov cocktail at the Temple Emanu-El in Reno on Nov.
30. The bomb burned only an adjacent sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Carl DeAmicis, 25, Christopher Hampton, 22, Scott Hudson 23, and
Daniel McIntosh, 19, pleaded guilty late Wednesday in U.S. District
Court to a series of federal charges, including conspiracy against
the rights of citizens. Each face up to 40 years in prison. Joshua
Kudlacek, 18, faces up to 35 years for his limited role in the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury indictment described the five as ''self-avowed
'skinheads' who advocated white supremacy and the oppression of
black, Jewish and other minority persons.''
</P>
<P>
   Sentencing is set for Oct. 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-13-00 2335 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000713.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAl Butler:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Al Butler, a former NBA player, died
Wednesday of cancer. He was 62.
</P>
<P>
   Butler was named All-American at Niagara University, and played
four seasons in the NBA for the Boston Celtics, New York Knicks and
Baltimore Bullets. He was playing for New York the night Wilt
Chamberlain set a record by scoring 100 points. Butler scored 8
points as a started in that game, March 2, 1962.
Ted Hampson:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Ted Hampson, a reporter for WBBM-AM and former
correspondent for The Associated Press, died Thursday after a
battle with colon cancer. He was 44.
</P>
<P>
   Hampson became WBBM's morning street reporter in 1995 and was
later assigned to cover the aftermath of the bombing of the federal
building in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining WBBM, Hampson spent more than a decade with The
Associated Press as a reporter in Washington and Chicago, and then
as the Midwest correspondent for the AP's national radio network.
</P>
<P>
   Hampson covered several presidential campaigns and traveled with
candidates including George Bush, Michael Dukakis and Richard
Gephardt. Among his many honors were reporting awards from the
Chicago Headline Club and the AP Broadcasters Association for his
coverage of the Mississippi River flood in 1993.
Paul H. Mussen:
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Paul Mussen, a pioneer in child psychology
who helped move the field toward a focus on social interactions
between parents and children, died July 7 after being hospitalized
for prostate cancer. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   Mussen was a professor of child psychology at the University of
California at Berkeley for 30 years. In 1956 he wrote ''Child
Development and Personality,'' which became a standard in the field
and made Mussen the top-selling author for Harper Textbooks for
many years.
</P>
<P>
   His other books included ''Handbook of Child Psychology'' in
1971, ''The Psychological Development of the Child'' in 1963 and
''Roots of Caring, Sharing and Helping'' in 1977.
Ras Shorty I:
</P>
<P>
   PORT-OF-SPAIN, Trinidad (AP) -- Ras Shorty I, who fused calypso
with an up-tempo beat that he said represented the true soul of
calypso, died Wednesday of bone cancer. He was 59.
</P>
<P>
   He was born Garfield Blackman and started singing calypso as
Lord Shorty.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of musicians later adopted his up-tempo ''soca'' beat,
which he called the ''Indianization of calypso,'' bringing together
the music of his Caribbean nation's two major ethnic groups,
descendants of African slaves and of indentured laborers from
India.
Wardell Winslow:
</P>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- Wardell Winslow, who served as managing
editor of the now-defunct Peninsula Times Tribune, died July 7 from
complications related to autoimmune hepatitis. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
   Winslow lived in Palo Alto and developed an expertise in the
history of the San Francisco Bay area. After his retirement in
1984, he wrote several books about Palo Alto and Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   He started his career in Palo Alto as a reporter in 1948,
earning $40 a week. When the Times and the Redwood City Tribune
merged to create the Peninsula Times Tribune in 1979, Winslow
became editorial pages editor. He was promoted to managing editor
in 1981.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-13-00 2335 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
